{"title_page": "Zoom Video Communications", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Zoom Video|2=Talk:Zoom Video Communications#Requested move 27 March 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{short description|American video communications company}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name               = Zoom Video Communications, Inc.\n| logo               = Zoom Communications Logo.svg\n| type               = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as          = {{nowrap|{{NASDAQ|ZM}} (Class A)}}\n| foundation         = 2011\n| location_city      = {{Nowrap|[[San Jose, California]]}}\n| key_people         = [[Eric Yuan]], founder and CEO\n| services           = Zoom Meetings<br />Zoom Premium Audio<br />Zoom Business IM<br />Zoom Video Webinar<br />Zoom Rooms<br />Zoom H.323/SIP Connector<br />Zoom Developer Platform\n| num_employees      = 1,958\n| num_employees_year = 2019\n| website            = {{URL|https://zoom.us}}\n}}\n[[File:DenverZoomAdvertizement.jpg|thumb|Zoom advertisement at [[Denver International Airport]]]]\n\n'''Zoom Video Communications''' is an American remote conferencing services company headquartered in [[San Jose, California]]. It provides a remote conferencing service that combines [[Videotelephony|video conferencing]], online meetings, chat, and mobile collaboration.<ref name=\"ume\">{{cite web|url=http://www.telepresenceoptions.com/2013/01/zooms_full_featured_ume_videoc/|title=Zoom's Full Featured UME Videoconferencing Platform Exceeds Expectations|publisher=Telepresence Options|date=27 January 2013|author=Maldow, David S.}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nZoom was founded in 2011 by [[Eric Yuan]], a lead engineer from [[Cisco Systems]] and its collaboration business unit [[Cisco Webex|WebEx]].<ref name=ume /> The service started in January 2013, and by May 2013 it claimed one million participants.<ref name=\"tmcnet1mil\">{{cite web | url=http://www.tmcnet.com/topics/articles/2013/05/23/339279-zoom-video-communications-reaches-1-million-participants.htm | title=Zoom Video Communications Reaches 1 Million Participants | publisher=TMCnet | date=23 May 2013 | author=Pleasant, Robbie}}</ref> During the first year of its release, Zoom established partnerships with [[Business-to-business|B2B]] collaboration software providers, such as [[Redbooth]] (then Teambox),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/06/18/teambox-adds-high-definition-video-conferencing-market-looks-for-deeper-collaboration/ |publisher=[[TechCrunch]]|title=Teambox Adds High-Definition Video Conferencing, Market Looks for Deeper Collaboration|date=18 June 2013}}</ref> and also created a program named \"Works with Zoom\", which established partnerships with multiple hardware and software vendors such as [[Logitech]], Vaddio,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hdproguide.com/vaddio-and-zoom-video-communications-partner-to-bring-collaboration-to-the-enterprise/ | title=Vaddio and Zoom Video Communications Partner to Bring Collaboration to The Enterprise | publisher=HD Pro Guide | date=25 July 2013 | accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> and [[InFocus]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conferencing.tmcnet.com/topics/conferencing/articles/347006-zoom-launches-program-with-top-communications-tech-companies.htm|publisher=[[TMCnet]]|title=Zoom Launches Program with Top Communications Tech Companies|date=25 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.enterprisenetworkingplanet.com/unified_communications/zoom-beefs-up-video-conferencing-strategy-with-new-partners.html | title=Zoom Beefs Up Video Conferencing Strategy with New Partners | publisher=Enterprise Networking Planet | date=29 July 2013 | accessdate=11 February 2015 | author=Chao, Jude}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20130723005656/en/Zoom-Video-Communications-Partners-Industry-Leading-Technology-Providers | title=Zoom Video Communications Partners with Industry-Leading Technology Providers | publisher=[[Business Wire]] | date=23 July 2013 | accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> \n\nBy June 2014, Zoom had 10 million users.<ref name=\"10million\">{{cite web | url=http://eir.dell.com/zoomed-10-million-participants/ | title=How We Zoomed to 10 Million Participants | publisher=Dell}}</ref> In February 2015, the number of participants utilizing Zoom Video Communication's chief product, Zoom Meetings, reached 40 million individuals, with 65,000 organizations subscribed. The company had hosted a total of 1 billion meeting minutes since it was established.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/zoom-raises-30m-in-series-c-funding-led-by-emergence-capital-1988574.htm | title=Zoom Raises $30M in Series C Funding Led by Emergence Capital | publisher=Market Wired}}</ref>\n\nOn February 4, 2015, Zoom Video Communications received [[US$]]30 million in [[Venture round|Series C]] funding. Participants in this funding round include Emergence Capital, Horizons Ventures ([[Li Ka-shing]]), [[Qualcomm Ventures]], [[Jerry Yang]], and [[Patrick Soon-Shiong]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2015/02/04/fast-growing-zoom-raises-30-million-for-online-video-conferencing/ | title=Fast-Growing Zoom Raises $30 Million for Online Video Conferencing | publisher=Wall Street Journal | date=4 February 2015 | author=Gage, Deborah}}</ref> In November 2015, former president of [[RingCentral]] David Berman was named president of Zoom Video Communications, and the founder and [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of [[Veeva Systems]], [[Peter Gassner]], joined Zoom's [[board of directors]].<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/zoom-names-new-president-david-berman-and-board-member-peter-gassner-2069595.htm | title=Zoom Names New President David Berman and Board Member Peter Gassner | publisher=MarketWired | date=3 November 2015 | accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Zoom had officially entered the [[Unicorn (finance)|unicorn]] club ($1 billion valuation) and attracted $100 million in Series D funding from [[Sequoia Capital]] at a billion dollar valuation. \n\nIn September 2017, Zoom hosted Zoomtopia 2017, Zoom's first annual user conference. Zoom announced a series of new products and partnerships, including Zoom's Partnership with Meta to integrate Zoom with Augmented Reality, integration with Slack and Workplace by Facebook, and first steps towards an artificial intelligence speech-to-text converter.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/09/26/zoom-brings-a-dash-of-augmented-reality-and-artificial-intelligence-to-meetings-in-latest-release/|title=Zoom brings a dash of augmented reality and artificial intelligence to meetings in latest&nbsp;release|last=Miller|first=Ron|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2017-11-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Zoom filed to go public on the NASDAQ;<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/03/22/zoom-a-profitable-unicorn-files-to-go-public/|title=Zoom, a profitable unicorn, files to go public|last=Clark|first=Kate|date=2019-03-22|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> on April 18, 2019, the company went public, with shares up more than 72%, with an [[Initial public offering]] of $36 a share.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/18/tech/zoom-ipo-video-conference/index.html|title=Zoom nearly reaches $16 billion in value after first day of trading|last=Business|first=Ahiza Garcia, Sara O'Brien and Jordan Valinsky|date=2019-04-18|website=CNN|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> The company was valued at just under $16 billion by the end of its IPO.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Use during the COVID-19 pandemic ===\n{{main|Coronavirus impact on teleconferencing}}\n\nIn early 2020, usage of Zoom increased sharply as schools and companies adopted the platform for [[Telecommuting|remote work]] in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) pandemic]], rising 67% from the start of the year to mid-March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/03/14/zoom-is-helping-schools-closing-due-coronavirus-fo.aspx|title=Zoom Is Helping Schools Closing Due to Coronavirus -- for Free|last=Vena|first=Danny|date=2020-03-14|website=The Motley Fool|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> Since the novel coronavirus pandemic has intensified, news outlets have reported that thousands of educational institutions switched to online classes using Zoom.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mervosh|first=Sarah|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/coronavirus-closings.html|title=Colleges and Universities Cancel Classes and Move Online Amid Coronavirus Fears|date=2020-03-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-26|last2=Swales|first2=Vanessa|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2020/03/20/schooling-rapidly-moves-online-across-country-concerns-rise-about-student-data-privacy/|title=As schooling rapidly moves online across the country, concerns rise about student data privacy|last=Strauss|first=Valerie|date=March 20, 2020|website=The Washington post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The company offered its services to K\u201312 schools free of charge in many countries.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexkonrad/2020/03/13/zoom-video-coronavirus-eric-yuan-schools/|title=Exclusive: Zoom CEO Eric Yuan Is Giving K-12 Schools His Videoconferencing Tools For Free|last=Konrad|first=Alex|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> These measures have contributed to a sharp rise in Zoom usage; for example, in one day, the Zoom app was downloaded 343,000 times with about 18% of those downloads originating in the United States.<ref name=\":5\" /> Zoom gained over 2.22 million users in the first months of 2020 which is more users than they amassed in the entirety of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/26/zoom-has-added-more-users-so-far-this-year-than-in-2019-bernstein.html|title=Zoom has added more videoconferencing users this year than in all of 2019 thanks to coronavirus, Bernstein says|last=Novet|first=Jordan|date=2020-02-26|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Consequently, by March 2020, Zoom shares increased to $160.98 per share which is a 263% increase from initial share prices when Zoom went public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/zoom-stock-price-surged-coronavirus-pandemic-video-work-from-home-2020-3-1029023594|title=Zoom Video has seen its stock spike more than 100% since January as coronavirus pushes millions to work from home (ZM)|last=Reinicke|first=Carmen|date=23 March 2020|website=markets.businessinsider.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nZoom also became a popular social platform over the course of the pandemic.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=Lorenz|first=Taylor|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/style/zoom-parties-coronavirus-memes.html|title=We Live in Zoom Now|date=2020-03-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-26|last2=Griffith|first2=Erin|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Isaac|first3=Mike}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/23/ok-zoomer-zoom-worlds-new-favourite-social-network-12443418/|title=Ok Zoomer: Why Zoom is the world's new favourite social network|last=Parsons|first=Jeff|date=2020-03-23|website=Metro|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Young people use the platform outside of the classroom setting.<ref name=\":4\" /> [[Generation Z|Gen Z]] and [[Millennials]] have connected with each other through events such as \"Zoom Blind Dates\", \"Zoom Recess\", and sharing Zoom related memes online,  such as in the [[Facebook]] group \"Zoom Memes for Self Quaranteens\".<ref name=\":4\" /> Zoom as a company has developed into an [[Internet meme|Internet Meme]] and students at a number of colleges and universities have spread memes about its use as \"Zoom University\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wagner|first=James|url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/2020/coronavirus-update-03-13|title=How Coronavirus Is Changing Our Daily Lives: Latest Updates|date=2020-03-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Lorenz|first=Taylor|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/style/zoom-parties-coronavirus-memes.html|title=We Live in Zoom Now|date=March 17, 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live|last2=Griffith|first2=Erin|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Isaac|first3=Mike}}</ref> Zoom has also gained popularity amongst older users and families separated by ongoing [[social distancing]] guidelines and mandates. These virtual social gatherings are often referred to as \"Zoom Parties\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/how-to-throw-zoom-party-custom-background-friends-family-2020-3|title=How to throw a perfect Zoom party with your friends and family|last=Tenbarge|first=Kat|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> \n\nWith the rise of videoconferencing, incidents of \"[[Zoombombing|{{Anchor|Zoombombing}}Zoombombing]]\", the practice of participants unexpectedly appearing in conferences and sending [[pornography]] or other offensive material to other attendees, have occurred,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2020/03/25/zoombombing-disrupts-online-classes-university-southern-california/|title=\u2018Zoombombing\u2019 disrupts online classes at University of Southern California|website=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-03-25/zoombombing-usc-classes-interrupted-racist-remarks|title=USC, school districts getting 'Zoom-bombed' with racist taunts, porn as they transition to online meetings|date=March 25, 2020|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/17/zoombombing/|title=Beware of \u2018ZoomBombing:\u2019 screensharing filth to video calls|date=March 18, 2020|website=TechCrunch}}</ref> causing some organizations to abandon the use of Zoom.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Taylor Lorenz|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/20/style/zoombombing-zoom-trolling.html|title=\u2018Zoombombing\u2019: When Video Conferences Go Wrong|work=The New York Times|accessdate=27 March 2020|language=en|quote=On Tuesday, Chipotle was forced to end a public Zoom chat that the brand had co-hosted with the musician Lauv after one participant began broadcasting pornography to hundreds of attendees [...] \u201cWe did encounter an unwanted \u2018Zoombomb\u2019 during one of our sessions so we moved our latest performances to a different platform.\u201d}}</ref>  Zoom has published a guide to reduce the chances of such incidents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.zoom.us/wordpress/2020/03/20/keep-the-party-crashers-from-crashing-your-zoom-event/|title=How to Keep the Party Crashers from Crashing Your Zoom Event|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\nZoom offers free video conferencing for up to 100 participants, with a 40-minute time limit. Paid subscriptions are available to allow more participants, increase the time limit, and obtain more advanced features. Zoom's [[Proprietary software|closed source]] software is claimed to be compliant with [[FedRAMP]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://convergentav.net/2018/07/10/zoom-achieves-fedramp-in-process-milestone/|title=Zoom Achieves FedRAMP \"In Process\" Milestone|date=2018-07-10|website=Convergent|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>, [[Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act|HIPAA]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hipaajournal.com/zoom-hipaa-compliant/|title=Is Zoom a HIPAA Compliant Video and Web Conferencing Platform?|date=2018-02-19|website=HIPAA Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>, [[Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act|PIPEDA]] and [[Personal Health Information Protection Act|PHIPA]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bitpipe.com/detail/RES/1548948281_430.html|title=Build patient engagement with compliant video conferencing|website=www.bitpipe.com|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>, and the [[General Data Protection Regulation|GDPR]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/360000126326-Official-Statement-EU-GDPR-Compliance|title=Official Statement: EU GDPR Compliance|website=Zoom Help Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> Zoom has received various industry recognitions for its products.<ref>{{cite web |title=Awards Archives |url=https://blog.zoom.us/wordpress/category/awards/ |website=Zoom blog |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nInitially, Zoom could host conferences with up to 15 video participants,<ref name=\"15participants\">{{cite web | url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10000872396390444443504577603383238616426?mg=reno64-wsj&url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB10000872396390444443504577603383238616426.html | title=A Chance To Call 15 Friends To Video Chat In High Def | publisher=Wall Street Journal | date=21 August 2012 | author=[[Walt Mossberg|Mossberg, Walter S.]]}}</ref> increased to 25 in January 2013, to 100 with version 2.5 in October 2015,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eweek.com/networking/zoom-doubles-capacity-of-video-conferencing-service-to-50.html | title=Zoom Doubles Capacity of Video Conferencing Service to 50 | publisher=eWeek | date=2 October 2015 | accessdate=19 November 2015 | author=Burt, Jeffrey}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://zoom.us/pricing|title=Video Conferencing, Web Conferencing, Webinars, Screen Sharing|website=Zoom Video|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-29}}</ref> and later to 1,000 for business customers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/skype-vs-zoom-which-video-chat-app-is-best-for-working-from-home/|title=Skype vs. Zoom: Which video chat app is best for working from home?|first=Shelby|last=Brown|date=10 March 2020|work=CNET|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>  Between 2015 and mid-2016, Zoom Video Communications announced native support for [[Skype for Business]] and integration with [[Slack (software)|Slack]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.zoom.us/wordpress/2015/08/13/zoom-slack-integration/|title=Announcement: Zoom Slack Integration|last=|first=|date=13 August 2015|website=Zoom Blog|publisher=|access-date=8 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/money/other/zoom-announces-native-skype-for-business-interoperability/ar-BBr50fP|title=Zoom Announces Native Skype for Business Interoperability|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Zoom announced integration of Zoom video conferencing with [[Salesforce]]'s [[customer relationship management]] platform, allowing salespeople to initiate such conferences with their [[sales lead]]s without leaving the application.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmcnet.com/channels/ip-phones/articles/409907-zoom-announces-salesforce-integration.htm|title=Zoom Announces Salesforce Integration|author=Delony, David|date=15 September 2015|publisher=TMCnet|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref> In April 2017, Zoom launched Telehealth, a scalable [[telehealth]] product allowing doctors to remotely visit their patients through video for consultation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://conferencing.tmcnet.com/topics/conferencing/articles/431502-zoom-introduces-new-telehealth-solution.htm |title=Zoom Introduces New Telehealth Solution |last=Young |first=Alicia |date=24 April 2017 |work=TMCnet |access-date=7 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2017/04/20/1311124/0/en/Zoom-Launches-Industry-s-First-Scalable-Cloud-Based-Video-Telehealth-Solution.html|title=Zoom Launches Industry's First Scalable Cloud-Based Video Telehealth Solution|first=Zoom Video Communications|last=Inc|date=April 20, 2017|website=GlobeNewswire News Room}}</ref> In May 2017, Zoom announced a partnership with [[Polycom]] that integrated Zoom's video meetings into Polycom's conferencing systems, enabling features such as multiple screen and device meetings, HD and wireless screen sharing, and calendar integration with Outlook, Google Calendar, and iCal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/polycom-zoom-forge-video-conferencing-collaboration-pact/|title=Polycom, Zoom forge video conferencing, collaboration pact {{!}} ZDNet|last=Dignan|first=Larry|date=2017-05-25|work=ZDNet|access-date=2017-11-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, NextTech AR Solutions acquired software company Jolokia and intends to integrate Zoom into Jolokia\u2019s Inferno platform.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/Globe%20Newswire/5da1d774de88096b425757d497fb32f2|title=NexTech AR Integrates Zoom Video Conferencing Into Remote Work & Learning Platform|last=NexTech AR Solutions Corp.|first=|date=2020-03-24|website=AP NEWS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> This integration would allow Zoom meetings to support up to 100,000 participants with \u201creal-time Q&A Plus immersive AR.\u201d<ref name=\":6\" /> Additional features include the ability to start a Zoom meeting from the Inferno platform and the incorporation of [[closed captioning]] in 64 languages to meeting recordings.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==Criticism==\n===Privacy===\nZoom has been criticized for its data collection practices,<ref>{{cite web |last1=St. John |first1=Allen |title=Zoom Calls Aren't as Private as You May Think. Here's What You Should Know. |url=https://www.consumerreports.org/video-conferencing-services/zoom-teleconferencing-privacy-concerns/ |website=Consumer Reports |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> which include its collection and storage of \"the content contained in cloud recordings, and instant messages, files, whiteboards\" as well as its enabling employers to monitor workers remotely;<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kate O'Flaherty |title=Zoom\u2019s A Lifeline During COVID-19: This Is Why It\u2019s Also A Privacy Risk |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kateoflahertyuk/2020/03/25/zooms-a-lifeline-during-covid-19-this-is-why-its-also-a-privacy-risk/#508f8eb428ba |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Forbes |date=25 March 2020 |language=en |quote=collects and stores personal data and shares it with third parties such as advertisers.  But Zoom\u2019s policy also covers what it labels \u201ccustomer content,\u201d or \"the content contained in cloud recordings, and instant messages, files, whiteboards ... shared while using the service.\"  This includes videos, transcripts that can be generated automatically, documents shared on screen, and the names of everyone on a call.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Morse |first1=Jack |title=Zoom is a work-from-home privacy disaster waiting to happen |url=https://mashable.com/article/zoom-conference-call-work-from-home-privacy-concerns/ |website=Mashable |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] warned that administrators can join any call at any time \"without in-the-moment consent or warning for the attendees of the call.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2020/03/what-you-should-know-about-online-tools-during-covid-19-crisis|title=What You Should Know About Online Tools During the COVID-19 Crisis|first=Lindsay|last=Oliver|date=March 19, 2020|website=Electronic Frontier Foundation}}</ref> The Ministry of Defence of the U.K. banned its use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/25/concern-zoom-video-conferencing-mod-bans-security-fears-12455327/|title=Concern over Zoom video conferencing after MoD bans it over security fears|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronairus-cabinet-talks-held-on-zoom-days-after-software-was-banned-by-ministry-of-defence-11963889|title=Coronavirus: Cabinet talks held on Zoom days after software was banned by Ministry of Defence|website=Sky News}}</ref> During signup for a Zoom free account, Zoom requires users to permit it to identify users with their personal information on Google and also offers to permanently delete their Google contacts.\n\nWidespread use of Zoom for online education during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|novel coronavirus pandemic]] increased concerns regarding students' data privacy and, in particular, their [[Personal data|personally identifiable information]].<ref name=\":2\" /> According to the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]], students\u2019 IP addresses, browsing history, academic progress, and biometric data may be at risk during the use of similar online learning services.<ref name=\":2\" /> Privacy experts are also concerned that the use of Zoom by schools and universities may raise issues regarding unauthorized surveillance of students and possible violations of students\u2019 rights under the [[Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act]] (FERPA).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2020/03/25/pivot-online-raises-concerns-ferpa-surveillance|title=Pivot to online raises concerns for FERPA, surveillance|last=St. Amour|first=Madeline|date=|website=www.insidehighered.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> The company claims that the video services are FERPA-compliant, and also claims that it collects and stores user data only to \"provide technical and operational support\".<ref name=\":3\" />  \n\nThe company's [[iOS]] app was found to be sending device analytics data to [[Facebook]] on startup, regardless of whether a Facebook account was being used with the service, and without mentioning it to the user.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/k7e599/zoom-ios-app-sends-data-to-facebook-even-if-you-dont-have-a-facebook-account|title=Zoom iOS App Sends Data to Facebook Even if You Don\u2019t Have a Facebook Account|last=Cox|first=Joseph|date=2020-03-26|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> On March 27, Zoom stated that it had been \"recently made aware that the Facebook [[Software development kit|SDK]] was collecting unnecessary device data\", and that it had patched the app to remove the SDK (which was primarily used for [[social login]] support) in order to address these concerns. The company stated that the SDK was only collecting information on the user's device specifications (such as model names and operating system versions), and was not collecting personal information.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/z3b745/zoom-removes-code-that-sends-data-to-facebook|title=Zoom Removes Code That Sends Data to Facebook|last=Cox|first=Joseph|date=2020-03-27|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nIn March, Zoom was sued in US Federal Court for illegally disclosing personal data to third parties including [[Facebook]]. According to the suit, Zoom\u2019s privacy policy doesn\u2019t explain to users that its app contains code that discloses information to [[Facebook]] and potentially other third parties. The company\u2019s \u201cwholly inadequate program design and security measures have resulted, and will continue to result, in unauthorized disclosure of its users\u2019 personal information,\u201d according to the complaint.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rosenblatt |first1=Joel |title=Zoom Sued for Allegedly Illegally Disclosing Personal Data |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/zoom-sued-for-allegedly-illegally-disclosing-personal-data |website=Bloomberg |publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\n=== Security ===\nZoom claims to use [[Advanced Encryption Standard]] 256-bit (AES 256) encryption.<ref name=\"aes128\">{{cite web | url=http://www.enterprisenetworkingplanet.com/unified_communications/zoom-aims-to-disrupt-video-conferencing-market.html | title=Zoom Aims to Disrupt Video Conferencing Market | publisher=Enterprise Networking Planet | date=18 June 2013 | author=Chao, Jude}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://zoom.us/feature|title=Video Conferencing, Web Conferencing, Webinars, Screen Sharing|website=Zoom Video|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-29}}</ref> AES is being used to protect an initial [[Transport Layer Security|TLS]] control connection to Zoom server  but the actual audio and video streams sent over UDP are not [[End-to-end encryption|end-to-end encrypted]]. Zoom claims to use \"end-to-end encryption\" in its marketing materials but later clarified they meant \"from Zoom end point to Zoom end point\" (meaning effectively between Zoom servers), which has been described as \"dishonest\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2020/03/31/zoom-meeting-encryption/|title=Zoom Meetings Aren\u2019t End-to-End Encrypted, Despite Misleading Marketing|last=Lee|first=Micah|last2=Grauer|first2=Yael|date=2020-03-31|website=The Intercept|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31|quote=Currently, it is not possible to enable E2E encryption for Zoom video meetings. (...) When we use the phrase \u2018End to End\u2019 in our other literature, it is in reference to the connection being encrypted from Zoom end point to Zoom end point.}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, a security vulnerability ({{CVE|2018-15715}}) was discovered<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2018-15715 |title=CVE-2018-15715 |website=National Vulnerability Database |access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref> that allowed a remote unauthenticated attacker to spoof UDP messages from a meeting attendee or Zoom server in order to invoke functionality in the target client. This would allow the attacker to remove attendees from meetings, spoof messages from users, or hijack shared screens.\n\nIn July 2019, security researcher Jonathan Leitschuh disclosed<ref>{{cite web |url=https://medium.com/@jonathan.leitschuh/zoom-zero-day-4-million-webcams-maybe-an-rce-just-get-them-to-visit-your-website-ac75c83f4ef5 |title=Zoom Zero Day: 4+ Million Webcams & maybe an RCE? Just get them to visit your website! |last=Leitschuh |first=Jonathan |date=2019-07-09 |website=Medium |language=en |access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref> a [[zero-day (computing)|zero-day]] vulnerability allowing any website to forcibly join a macOS user to a Zoom call, with their video camera activated, without the user's permission. In addition, attempts to uninstall the Zoom client on macOS would prompt the software to re-install automatically in the background, using a hidden web server that was set up on the machine during the first installation and remained active even after attempting to remove the client. After receiving public criticism, Zoom updated their software to remove the vulnerability and the hidden webserver, allowing complete uninstallation.<ref name=\"Anderson 2019\">{{cite web | last=Anderson | first=Tim | title=Anyone for unintended Chat Roulette? Zoom installs hidden Mac web server to allow auto-join video conferencing | website=The Register | date=2019-07-09 | url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2019/07/09/zooms_hidden_mac_web_server_allows_autojoin_conferencing_exploit/ | access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nThe popularity of Zoom caused a \"sharp\" increase in Zoom-related [[phishing]] scams. The number of [[Domain name|domains]] containing the name \"Zoom\" showed a sharp increase during the Covid-19 pandemic. Many of these were used to make fake Zoom websites and links for the purposes of stealing personal information. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.computerweekly.com/news/252480806/Coronavirus-Warning-over-surge-in-Zoom-security-incidents|title=Coronavirus: Warning over surge in Zoom security incidents|last=Scroxton|first=Alex|date=30 March 2020|website=ComputerWeekly.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n====New York State Investigation====\nThe New York attorney general launched an inquiry into Zoom's privacy practices.  The company responded that \u00abWe appreciate the New York attorney general\u2019s engagement on these issues\u00bb.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/technology/new-york-attorney-general-zoom-privacy.html?partner=IFTTT</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://zoom.us/}}\n\n{{Finance links\n| name      = Zoom Video Communications, Inc.\n| symbol    = ZM\n| reuters   = ZM.O\n| bloomberg = ZM:US\n| sec_cik   = ZM\n| yahoo     = ZM\n| google    = ZM\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Software companies established in 2011]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 2011]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Software companies based in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Companies based in San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:Web conferencing]]\n[[Category:Videotelephony]]\n[[Category:2019 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n[[Category:Software companies of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Zoom Video|2=Talk:Zoom Video Communications#Requested move 27 March 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{short description|American video communications company}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name               = Zoom Video Communications, Inc.\n| logo               = Zoom Communications Logo.svg\n| type               = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as          = {{nowrap|{{NASDAQ|ZM}} (Class A)}}\n| foundation         = 2011\n| location_city      = {{Nowrap|[[San Jose, California]]}}\n| key_people         = [[Eric Yuan]], founder and CEO\n| services           = Zoom Meetings<br />Zoom Premium Audio<br />Zoom Business IM<br />Zoom Video Webinar<br />Zoom Rooms<br />Zoom H.323/SIP Connector<br />Zoom Developer Platform\n| num_employees      = 1,958\n| num_employees_year = 2019\n| website            = {{URL|https://zoom.us}}\n}}\n[[File:DenverZoomAdvertizement.jpg|thumb|Zoom advertisement at [[Denver International Airport]]]]\n\n'''Zoom Video Communications''' is an American remote conferencing services company headquartered in [[San Jose, California]]. It provides a remote conferencing service that combines [[Videotelephony|video conferencing]], online meetings, chat, and mobile collaboration.<ref name=\"ume\">{{cite web|url=http://www.telepresenceoptions.com/2013/01/zooms_full_featured_ume_videoc/|title=Zoom's Full Featured UME Videoconferencing Platform Exceeds Expectations|publisher=Telepresence Options|date=27 January 2013|author=Maldow, David S.}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nZoom was founded in 2011 by [[Eric Yuan]], a lead engineer from [[Cisco Systems]] and its collaboration business unit [[Cisco Webex|WebEx]].<ref name=ume /> The service started in January 2013, and by May 2013 it claimed one million participants.<ref name=\"tmcnet1mil\">{{cite web | url=http://www.tmcnet.com/topics/articles/2013/05/23/339279-zoom-video-communications-reaches-1-million-participants.htm | title=Zoom Video Communications Reaches 1 Million Participants | publisher=TMCnet | date=23 May 2013 | author=Pleasant, Robbie}}</ref> During the first year of its release, Zoom established partnerships with [[Business-to-business|B2B]] collaboration software providers, such as [[Redbooth]] (then Teambox),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/06/18/teambox-adds-high-definition-video-conferencing-market-looks-for-deeper-collaboration/ |publisher=[[TechCrunch]]|title=Teambox Adds High-Definition Video Conferencing, Market Looks for Deeper Collaboration|date=18 June 2013}}</ref> and also created a program named \"Works with Zoom\", which established partnerships with multiple hardware and software vendors such as [[Logitech]], Vaddio,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hdproguide.com/vaddio-and-zoom-video-communications-partner-to-bring-collaboration-to-the-enterprise/ | title=Vaddio and Zoom Video Communications Partner to Bring Collaboration to The Enterprise | publisher=HD Pro Guide | date=25 July 2013 | accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> and [[InFocus]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conferencing.tmcnet.com/topics/conferencing/articles/347006-zoom-launches-program-with-top-communications-tech-companies.htm|publisher=[[TMCnet]]|title=Zoom Launches Program with Top Communications Tech Companies|date=25 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.enterprisenetworkingplanet.com/unified_communications/zoom-beefs-up-video-conferencing-strategy-with-new-partners.html | title=Zoom Beefs Up Video Conferencing Strategy with New Partners | publisher=Enterprise Networking Planet | date=29 July 2013 | accessdate=11 February 2015 | author=Chao, Jude}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20130723005656/en/Zoom-Video-Communications-Partners-Industry-Leading-Technology-Providers | title=Zoom Video Communications Partners with Industry-Leading Technology Providers | publisher=[[Business Wire]] | date=23 July 2013 | accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> \n\nBy June 2014, Zoom had 10 million users.<ref name=\"10million\">{{cite web | url=http://eir.dell.com/zoomed-10-million-participants/ | title=How We Zoomed to 10 Million Participants | publisher=Dell}}</ref> In February 2015, the number of participants utilizing Zoom Video Communication's chief product, Zoom Meetings, reached 40 million individuals, with 65,000 organizations subscribed. The company had hosted a total of 1 billion meeting minutes since it was established.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/zoom-raises-30m-in-series-c-funding-led-by-emergence-capital-1988574.htm | title=Zoom Raises $30M in Series C Funding Led by Emergence Capital | publisher=Market Wired}}</ref>\n\nOn February 4, 2015, Zoom Video Communications received [[US$]]30 million in [[Venture round|Series C]] funding. Participants in this funding round include Emergence Capital, Horizons Ventures ([[Li Ka-shing]]), [[Qualcomm Ventures]], [[Jerry Yang]], and [[Patrick Soon-Shiong]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2015/02/04/fast-growing-zoom-raises-30-million-for-online-video-conferencing/ | title=Fast-Growing Zoom Raises $30 Million for Online Video Conferencing | publisher=Wall Street Journal | date=4 February 2015 | author=Gage, Deborah}}</ref> In November 2015, former president of [[RingCentral]] David Berman was named president of Zoom Video Communications, and the founder and [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of [[Veeva Systems]], [[Peter Gassner]], joined Zoom's [[board of directors]].<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/zoom-names-new-president-david-berman-and-board-member-peter-gassner-2069595.htm | title=Zoom Names New President David Berman and Board Member Peter Gassner | publisher=MarketWired | date=3 November 2015 | accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Zoom had officially entered the [[Unicorn (finance)|unicorn]] club ($1 billion valuation) and attracted $100 million in Series D funding from [[Sequoia Capital]] at a billion dollar valuation. \n\nIn September 2017, Zoom hosted Zoomtopia 2017, Zoom's first annual user conference. Zoom announced a series of new products and partnerships, including Zoom's Partnership with Meta to integrate Zoom with Augmented Reality, integration with Slack and Workplace by Facebook, and first steps towards an artificial intelligence speech-to-text converter.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/09/26/zoom-brings-a-dash-of-augmented-reality-and-artificial-intelligence-to-meetings-in-latest-release/|title=Zoom brings a dash of augmented reality and artificial intelligence to meetings in latest&nbsp;release|last=Miller|first=Ron|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2017-11-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Zoom filed to go public on the NASDAQ;<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/03/22/zoom-a-profitable-unicorn-files-to-go-public/|title=Zoom, a profitable unicorn, files to go public|last=Clark|first=Kate|date=2019-03-22|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> on April 18, 2019, the company went public, with shares up more than 72%, with an [[Initial public offering]] of $36 a share.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/18/tech/zoom-ipo-video-conference/index.html|title=Zoom nearly reaches $16 billion in value after first day of trading|last=Business|first=Ahiza Garcia, Sara O'Brien and Jordan Valinsky|date=2019-04-18|website=CNN|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> The company was valued at just under $16 billion by the end of its IPO.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Use during the COVID-19 pandemic ===\n{{main|Coronavirus impact on teleconferencing}}\n\nIn early 2020, usage of Zoom increased sharply as schools and companies adopted the platform for [[Telecommuting|remote work]] in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) pandemic]], rising 67% from the start of the year to mid-March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/03/14/zoom-is-helping-schools-closing-due-coronavirus-fo.aspx|title=Zoom Is Helping Schools Closing Due to Coronavirus -- for Free|last=Vena|first=Danny|date=2020-03-14|website=The Motley Fool|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> Since the novel coronavirus pandemic has intensified, news outlets have reported that thousands of educational institutions switched to online classes using Zoom.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mervosh|first=Sarah|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/coronavirus-closings.html|title=Colleges and Universities Cancel Classes and Move Online Amid Coronavirus Fears|date=2020-03-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-26|last2=Swales|first2=Vanessa|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2020/03/20/schooling-rapidly-moves-online-across-country-concerns-rise-about-student-data-privacy/|title=As schooling rapidly moves online across the country, concerns rise about student data privacy|last=Strauss|first=Valerie|date=March 20, 2020|website=The Washington post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The company offered its services to K\u201312 schools free of charge in many countries.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexkonrad/2020/03/13/zoom-video-coronavirus-eric-yuan-schools/|title=Exclusive: Zoom CEO Eric Yuan Is Giving K-12 Schools His Videoconferencing Tools For Free|last=Konrad|first=Alex|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> These measures have contributed to a sharp rise in Zoom usage; for example, in one day, the Zoom app was downloaded 343,000 times with about 18% of those downloads originating in the United States.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nZoom also became a popular social platform over the course of the pandemic.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=Lorenz|first=Taylor|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/style/zoom-parties-coronavirus-memes.html|title=We Live in Zoom Now|date=2020-03-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-26|last2=Griffith|first2=Erin|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Isaac|first3=Mike}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/23/ok-zoomer-zoom-worlds-new-favourite-social-network-12443418/|title=Ok Zoomer: Why Zoom is the world's new favourite social network|last=Parsons|first=Jeff|date=2020-03-23|website=Metro|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Young people use the platform outside of the classroom setting.<ref name=\":4\" /> [[Generation Z|Gen Z]] and [[Millennials]] have connected with each other through events such as \"Zoom Blind Dates\", \"Zoom Recess\", and sharing Zoom related memes online,  such as in the [[Facebook]] group \"Zoom Memes for Self Quaranteens\".<ref name=\":4\" /> Zoom as a company has developed into an [[Internet meme|Internet Meme]] and students at a number of colleges and universities have spread memes about its use as \"Zoom University\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wagner|first=James|url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/2020/coronavirus-update-03-13|title=How Coronavirus Is Changing Our Daily Lives: Latest Updates|date=2020-03-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Lorenz|first=Taylor|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/style/zoom-parties-coronavirus-memes.html|title=We Live in Zoom Now|date=March 17, 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live|last2=Griffith|first2=Erin|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Isaac|first3=Mike}}</ref> Zoom has also gained popularity amongst older users and families separated by ongoing [[social distancing]] guidelines and mandates. These virtual social gatherings are often referred to as \"Zoom Parties\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/how-to-throw-zoom-party-custom-background-friends-family-2020-3|title=How to throw a perfect Zoom party with your friends and family|last=Tenbarge|first=Kat|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> \n\nWith the rise of videoconferencing, incidents of \"[[Zoombombing|{{Anchor|Zoombombing}}Zoombombing]]\", the practice of participants unexpectedly appearing in conferences and sending [[pornography]] or other offensive material to other attendees, have occurred,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2020/03/25/zoombombing-disrupts-online-classes-university-southern-california/|title=\u2018Zoombombing\u2019 disrupts online classes at University of Southern California|website=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-03-25/zoombombing-usc-classes-interrupted-racist-remarks|title=USC, school districts getting 'Zoom-bombed' with racist taunts, porn as they transition to online meetings|date=March 25, 2020|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/17/zoombombing/|title=Beware of \u2018ZoomBombing:\u2019 screensharing filth to video calls|date=March 18, 2020|website=TechCrunch}}</ref> causing some organizations to abandon the use of Zoom.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Taylor Lorenz|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/20/style/zoombombing-zoom-trolling.html|title=\u2018Zoombombing\u2019: When Video Conferences Go Wrong|work=The New York Times|accessdate=27 March 2020|language=en|quote=On Tuesday, Chipotle was forced to end a public Zoom chat that the brand had co-hosted with the musician Lauv after one participant began broadcasting pornography to hundreds of attendees [...] \u201cWe did encounter an unwanted \u2018Zoombomb\u2019 during one of our sessions so we moved our latest performances to a different platform.\u201d}}</ref>  Zoom has published a guide to reduce the chances of such incidents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.zoom.us/wordpress/2020/03/20/keep-the-party-crashers-from-crashing-your-zoom-event/|title=How to Keep the Party Crashers from Crashing Your Zoom Event|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\nZoom offers free video conferencing for up to 100 participants, with a 40-minute time limit. Paid subscriptions are available to allow more participants, increase the time limit, and obtain more advanced features. Zoom's [[Proprietary software|closed source]] software is claimed to be compliant with [[FedRAMP]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://convergentav.net/2018/07/10/zoom-achieves-fedramp-in-process-milestone/|title=Zoom Achieves FedRAMP \"In Process\" Milestone|date=2018-07-10|website=Convergent|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>, [[Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act|HIPAA]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hipaajournal.com/zoom-hipaa-compliant/|title=Is Zoom a HIPAA Compliant Video and Web Conferencing Platform?|date=2018-02-19|website=HIPAA Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>, [[Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act|PIPEDA]] and [[Personal Health Information Protection Act|PHIPA]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bitpipe.com/detail/RES/1548948281_430.html|title=Build patient engagement with compliant video conferencing|website=www.bitpipe.com|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>, and the [[General Data Protection Regulation|GDPR]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/360000126326-Official-Statement-EU-GDPR-Compliance|title=Official Statement: EU GDPR Compliance|website=Zoom Help Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> Zoom has received various industry recognitions for its products.<ref>{{cite web |title=Awards Archives |url=https://blog.zoom.us/wordpress/category/awards/ |website=Zoom blog |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nInitially, Zoom could host conferences with up to 15 video participants,<ref name=\"15participants\">{{cite web | url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10000872396390444443504577603383238616426?mg=reno64-wsj&url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB10000872396390444443504577603383238616426.html | title=A Chance To Call 15 Friends To Video Chat In High Def | publisher=Wall Street Journal | date=21 August 2012 | author=[[Walt Mossberg|Mossberg, Walter S.]]}}</ref> increased to 25 in January 2013, to 100 with version 2.5 in October 2015,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eweek.com/networking/zoom-doubles-capacity-of-video-conferencing-service-to-50.html | title=Zoom Doubles Capacity of Video Conferencing Service to 50 | publisher=eWeek | date=2 October 2015 | accessdate=19 November 2015 | author=Burt, Jeffrey}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://zoom.us/pricing|title=Video Conferencing, Web Conferencing, Webinars, Screen Sharing|website=Zoom Video|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-29}}</ref> and later to 1,000 for business customers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/skype-vs-zoom-which-video-chat-app-is-best-for-working-from-home/|title=Skype vs. Zoom: Which video chat app is best for working from home?|first=Shelby|last=Brown|date=10 March 2020|work=CNET|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>  Between 2015 and mid-2016, Zoom Video Communications announced native support for [[Skype for Business]] and integration with [[Slack (software)|Slack]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.zoom.us/wordpress/2015/08/13/zoom-slack-integration/|title=Announcement: Zoom Slack Integration|last=|first=|date=13 August 2015|website=Zoom Blog|publisher=|access-date=8 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/money/other/zoom-announces-native-skype-for-business-interoperability/ar-BBr50fP|title=Zoom Announces Native Skype for Business Interoperability|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Zoom announced integration of Zoom video conferencing with [[Salesforce]]'s [[customer relationship management]] platform, allowing salespeople to initiate such conferences with their [[sales lead]]s without leaving the application.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmcnet.com/channels/ip-phones/articles/409907-zoom-announces-salesforce-integration.htm|title=Zoom Announces Salesforce Integration|author=Delony, David|date=15 September 2015|publisher=TMCnet|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref> In April 2017, Zoom launched Telehealth, a scalable [[telehealth]] product allowing doctors to remotely visit their patients through video for consultation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://conferencing.tmcnet.com/topics/conferencing/articles/431502-zoom-introduces-new-telehealth-solution.htm |title=Zoom Introduces New Telehealth Solution |last=Young |first=Alicia |date=24 April 2017 |work=TMCnet |access-date=7 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2017/04/20/1311124/0/en/Zoom-Launches-Industry-s-First-Scalable-Cloud-Based-Video-Telehealth-Solution.html|title=Zoom Launches Industry's First Scalable Cloud-Based Video Telehealth Solution|first=Zoom Video Communications|last=Inc|date=April 20, 2017|website=GlobeNewswire News Room}}</ref> In May 2017, Zoom announced a partnership with [[Polycom]] that integrated Zoom's video meetings into Polycom's conferencing systems, enabling features such as multiple screen and device meetings, HD and wireless screen sharing, and calendar integration with Outlook, Google Calendar, and iCal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/polycom-zoom-forge-video-conferencing-collaboration-pact/|title=Polycom, Zoom forge video conferencing, collaboration pact {{!}} ZDNet|last=Dignan|first=Larry|date=2017-05-25|work=ZDNet|access-date=2017-11-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, NextTech AR Solutions acquired software company Jolokia and intends to integrate Zoom into Jolokia\u2019s Inferno platform.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/Globe%20Newswire/5da1d774de88096b425757d497fb32f2|title=NexTech AR Integrates Zoom Video Conferencing Into Remote Work & Learning Platform|last=NexTech AR Solutions Corp.|first=|date=2020-03-24|website=AP NEWS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> This integration would allow Zoom meetings to support up to 100,000 participants with \u201creal-time Q&A Plus immersive AR.\u201d<ref name=\":6\" /> Additional features include the ability to start a Zoom meeting from the Inferno platform and the incorporation of [[closed captioning]] in 64 languages to meeting recordings.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==Criticism==\n===Privacy===\nZoom has been criticized for its data collection practices,<ref>{{cite web |last1=St. John |first1=Allen |title=Zoom Calls Aren't as Private as You May Think. Here's What You Should Know. |url=https://www.consumerreports.org/video-conferencing-services/zoom-teleconferencing-privacy-concerns/ |website=Consumer Reports |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> which include its collection and storage of \"the content contained in cloud recordings, and instant messages, files, whiteboards\" as well as its enabling employers to monitor workers remotely;<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kate O'Flaherty |title=Zoom\u2019s A Lifeline During COVID-19: This Is Why It\u2019s Also A Privacy Risk |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kateoflahertyuk/2020/03/25/zooms-a-lifeline-during-covid-19-this-is-why-its-also-a-privacy-risk/#508f8eb428ba |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Forbes |date=25 March 2020 |language=en |quote=collects and stores personal data and shares it with third parties such as advertisers.  But Zoom\u2019s policy also covers what it labels \u201ccustomer content,\u201d or \"the content contained in cloud recordings, and instant messages, files, whiteboards ... shared while using the service.\"  This includes videos, transcripts that can be generated automatically, documents shared on screen, and the names of everyone on a call.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Morse |first1=Jack |title=Zoom is a work-from-home privacy disaster waiting to happen |url=https://mashable.com/article/zoom-conference-call-work-from-home-privacy-concerns/ |website=Mashable |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] warned that administrators can join any call at any time \"without in-the-moment consent or warning for the attendees of the call.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2020/03/what-you-should-know-about-online-tools-during-covid-19-crisis|title=What You Should Know About Online Tools During the COVID-19 Crisis|first=Lindsay|last=Oliver|date=March 19, 2020|website=Electronic Frontier Foundation}}</ref> The Ministry of Defence of the U.K. banned its use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/25/concern-zoom-video-conferencing-mod-bans-security-fears-12455327/|title=Concern over Zoom video conferencing after MoD bans it over security fears|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronairus-cabinet-talks-held-on-zoom-days-after-software-was-banned-by-ministry-of-defence-11963889|title=Coronavirus: Cabinet talks held on Zoom days after software was banned by Ministry of Defence|website=Sky News}}</ref> During signup for a Zoom free account, Zoom requires users to permit it to identify users with their personal information on Google and also offers to permanently delete their Google contacts.\n\nWidespread use of Zoom for online education during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|novel coronavirus pandemic]] increased concerns regarding students' data privacy and, in particular, their [[Personal data|personally identifiable information]].<ref name=\":2\" /> According to the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]], students\u2019 IP addresses, browsing history, academic progress, and biometric data may be at risk during the use of similar online learning services.<ref name=\":2\" /> Privacy experts are also concerned that the use of Zoom by schools and universities may raise issues regarding unauthorized surveillance of students and possible violations of students\u2019 rights under the [[Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act]] (FERPA).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2020/03/25/pivot-online-raises-concerns-ferpa-surveillance|title=Pivot to online raises concerns for FERPA, surveillance|last=St. Amour|first=Madeline|date=|website=www.insidehighered.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> The company claims that the video services are FERPA-compliant, and also claims that it collects and stores user data only to \"provide technical and operational support\".<ref name=\":3\" />  \n\nThe company's [[iOS]] app was found to be sending device analytics data to [[Facebook]] on startup, regardless of whether a Facebook account was being used with the service, and without mentioning it to the user.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/k7e599/zoom-ios-app-sends-data-to-facebook-even-if-you-dont-have-a-facebook-account|title=Zoom iOS App Sends Data to Facebook Even if You Don\u2019t Have a Facebook Account|last=Cox|first=Joseph|date=2020-03-26|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> On March 27, Zoom stated that it had been \"recently made aware that the Facebook [[Software development kit|SDK]] was collecting unnecessary device data\", and that it had patched the app to remove the SDK (which was primarily used for [[social login]] support) in order to address these concerns. The company stated that the SDK was only collecting information on the user's device specifications (such as model names and operating system versions), and was not collecting personal information.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/z3b745/zoom-removes-code-that-sends-data-to-facebook|title=Zoom Removes Code That Sends Data to Facebook|last=Cox|first=Joseph|date=2020-03-27|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nIn March, Zoom was sued in US Federal Court for illegally disclosing personal data to third parties including [[Facebook]]. According to the suit, Zoom\u2019s privacy policy doesn\u2019t explain to users that its app contains code that discloses information to [[Facebook]] and potentially other third parties. The company\u2019s \u201cwholly inadequate program design and security measures have resulted, and will continue to result, in unauthorized disclosure of its users\u2019 personal information,\u201d according to the complaint.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rosenblatt |first1=Joel |title=Zoom Sued for Allegedly Illegally Disclosing Personal Data |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/zoom-sued-for-allegedly-illegally-disclosing-personal-data |website=Bloomberg |publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\n=== Security ===\nZoom claims to use [[Advanced Encryption Standard]] 256-bit (AES 256) encryption.<ref name=\"aes128\">{{cite web | url=http://www.enterprisenetworkingplanet.com/unified_communications/zoom-aims-to-disrupt-video-conferencing-market.html | title=Zoom Aims to Disrupt Video Conferencing Market | publisher=Enterprise Networking Planet | date=18 June 2013 | author=Chao, Jude}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://zoom.us/feature|title=Video Conferencing, Web Conferencing, Webinars, Screen Sharing|website=Zoom Video|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-29}}</ref> AES is being used to protect an initial [[Transport Layer Security|TLS]] control connection to Zoom server  but the actual audio and video streams sent over UDP are not [[End-to-end encryption|end-to-end encrypted]]. Zoom claims to use \"end-to-end encryption\" in its marketing materials but later clarified they meant \"from Zoom end point to Zoom end point\" (meaning effectively between Zoom servers), which has been described as \"dishonest\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2020/03/31/zoom-meeting-encryption/|title=Zoom Meetings Aren\u2019t End-to-End Encrypted, Despite Misleading Marketing|last=Lee|first=Micah|last2=Grauer|first2=Yael|date=2020-03-31|website=The Intercept|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31|quote=Currently, it is not possible to enable E2E encryption for Zoom video meetings. (...) When we use the phrase \u2018End to End\u2019 in our other literature, it is in reference to the connection being encrypted from Zoom end point to Zoom end point.}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, a security vulnerability ({{CVE|2018-15715}}) was discovered<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2018-15715 |title=CVE-2018-15715 |website=National Vulnerability Database |access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref> that allowed a remote unauthenticated attacker to spoof UDP messages from a meeting attendee or Zoom server in order to invoke functionality in the target client. This would allow the attacker to remove attendees from meetings, spoof messages from users, or hijack shared screens.\n\nIn July 2019, security researcher Jonathan Leitschuh disclosed<ref>{{cite web |url=https://medium.com/@jonathan.leitschuh/zoom-zero-day-4-million-webcams-maybe-an-rce-just-get-them-to-visit-your-website-ac75c83f4ef5 |title=Zoom Zero Day: 4+ Million Webcams & maybe an RCE? Just get them to visit your website! |last=Leitschuh |first=Jonathan |date=2019-07-09 |website=Medium |language=en |access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref> a [[zero-day (computing)|zero-day]] vulnerability allowing any website to forcibly join a macOS user to a Zoom call, with their video camera activated, without the user's permission. In addition, attempts to uninstall the Zoom client on macOS would prompt the software to re-install automatically in the background, using a hidden web server that was set up on the machine during the first installation and remained active even after attempting to remove the client. After receiving public criticism, Zoom updated their software to remove the vulnerability and the hidden webserver, allowing complete uninstallation.<ref name=\"Anderson 2019\">{{cite web | last=Anderson | first=Tim | title=Anyone for unintended Chat Roulette? Zoom installs hidden Mac web server to allow auto-join video conferencing | website=The Register | date=2019-07-09 | url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2019/07/09/zooms_hidden_mac_web_server_allows_autojoin_conferencing_exploit/ | access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nThe popularity of Zoom caused a \"sharp\" increase in Zoom-related [[phishing]] scams. The number of [[Domain name|domains]] containing the name \"Zoom\" showed a sharp increase during the Covid-19 pandemic. Many of these were used to make fake Zoom websites and links for the purposes of stealing personal information. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.computerweekly.com/news/252480806/Coronavirus-Warning-over-surge-in-Zoom-security-incidents|title=Coronavirus: Warning over surge in Zoom security incidents|last=Scroxton|first=Alex|date=30 March 2020|website=ComputerWeekly.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n====New York State Investigation====\nThe New York attorney general launched an inquiry into Zoom's privacy practices.  The company responded that \u00abWe appreciate the New York attorney general\u2019s engagement on these issues\u00bb.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/technology/new-york-attorney-general-zoom-privacy.html?partner=IFTTT</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://zoom.us/}}\n\n{{Finance links\n| name      = Zoom Video Communications, Inc.\n| symbol    = ZM\n| reuters   = ZM.O\n| bloomberg = ZM:US\n| sec_cik   = ZM\n| yahoo     = ZM\n| google    = ZM\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Software companies established in 2011]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 2011]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Software companies based in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Companies based in San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:Web conferencing]]\n[[Category:Videotelephony]]\n[[Category:2019 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n[[Category:Software companies of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Saghakian", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a couple sentences regarding increases in Zoom users and Zoom stock.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zoom_Video_Communications"}
{"title_page": "The Wonderful 101", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = The Wonderful 101\n| image = Wonderful 101 box artwork.jpg\n| caption = North American Wii U box art\n| developer = [[PlatinumGames]]\n| publisher = {{ubl|[[Nintendo]] (Wii U)|PlatinumGames (NS, Win, PS4)}}\n| director = [[Hideki Kamiya]]\n| producer = {{ubl|[[Atsushi Inaba]]|Hitoshi Yamagami}}\n| designer = Hiroshi Shibata\n| programmer =\n| artist = {{ubl|Yuka Kotaki|Ryo Koizumi}}\n| writer = Hideki Kamiya\n| composer = {{ubl|[[Norihiko Hibino]]|Hiroshi Yamaguchi|Rei Kondoh|Akira Takizawa|Hitomi Kurokawa|Masato Kouda}}\n| platforms = [[Wii U]], [[Nintendo Switch]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]]\n| released = '''Wii U'''{{vgrelease|EU|August 23, 2013<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |last=Karmali |first=Luke |url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2013/05/17/the-wonderful-101-release-date-announced |title=The Wonderful 101 Release Date Announced |website=IGN |date=May 17, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Hzl7kVZV?url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/05/17/the-wonderful-101-release-date-announced |archive-date=July 10, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>|[[Japan|JP]]/[[Australasia|AU]]|August 24, 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.com.au/index.php?action=news&nid=2903&pageID=6|title=NINTENDO ANNOUNCES EXCLUSIVE WORLDWIDE PARTNERSHIP WITH SEGA FOR UPCOMING SONIC THE HEDGEHOG GAMES|publisher=Nintendo Australia Pty. Ltd.|date=May 18, 2013|accessdate=May 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908051626/http://www.nintendo.com.au/index.php?action=news&nid=2903&pageID=6|archive-date=September 8, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>|NA|September 15, 2013<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>}}\n'''Switch, Windows, PS4'''{{vgrelease|NA|May 19, 2020|EU|May 22, 2020|JP|June 11, 2020}}\n| genre = [[Action-adventure]], [[hack and slash]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n{{nihongo foot|'''''The Wonderful 101'''''|\u30b6\u30fb\u30ef\u30f3\u30c0\u30d5\u30eb \u30ef\u30f3\u30fb\u30aa\u30fc\u30fb\u30ef\u30f3|Za Wandafuru Wan \u014c Wan|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is an [[action-adventure game]] developed by [[PlatinumGames]] and published by [[Nintendo]] for the [[Wii U]]. The game was directed by [[Hideki Kamiya]] and produced by [[Atsushi Inaba]]; the pair also worked together on the ''[[Viewtiful Joe]]'' series and ''[[\u014ckami]]''. It was released in August 2013 in all major regions except North America, where it released the following month. ''The Wonderful 101'' received generally positive reviews, but failed to meet sales expectations.\n\nIn February 2020, PlatinumGames announced a remastered version for [[Nintendo Switch]], [[Microsoft Windows]] and [[PlayStation 4]], financed through [[crowdfunding]], with a planned release in May 2020.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:The Wonderful 101 Unite Morph battle screenshot.png|thumb|Screenshot of an earlier version of the game depicting a \"Unite Morph\" ability used to battle an opponent. The heroes have combined to form \"Unite Hand\", which is shown punching a large enemy called the Diedough-Goo.]]\n\nIn ''The Wonderful 101'', players control a horde of superheroes from an [[Isometric graphics in video games and pixel art|isometric]] viewpoint and can turn them into various objects called \"Unite Morphs.\" As levels progress, players must explore each stage to find helpless citizens and recruit them to join their army of heroes. The more heroes gathered, the greater the special morph powers can be. At the cost of depleting their battery meter, players can use \"Unite Morph\" forms to defeat enemies, solve puzzles, or traverse the environment. The meter can be recharged by performing normal attacks or by picking up batteries dropped by a defeated enemy. Enemies will also drop \"O parts\" (the in-game currency used to buy upgrades), new \"Unite Morph\" abilities and items. To transform the horde of heroes, the appropriate symbol is drawn on the [[Wii U GamePad]]'s touchscreen or right [[analog stick]], such as an \u201cL\u201d for a gun or a squiggly line for a whip. In specified areas, the GamePad (by default) is used to change the view to a traditional, third-person angle and better explore tighter environments, such as those found indoors and inside caves.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://e3.nintendo.com/games/#/wiiu/projectp-100 |title=Nintendo All-Access @ E3 2012 - Games |website=E3.nintendo.com |accessdate=July 9, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120920061728/http://e3.nintendo.com/games/#/wiiu/projectp-100 |archivedate=September 20, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"nintendolife2\">{{cite web |last=Meyer |first=Lee |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2013/06/hands_on_the_wonderful_101/ |title=Hands On: The Wonderful 101 |work=Nintendo Life |date=June 26, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920093231/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2013/06/hands_on_the_wonderful_101 |archive-date=September 20, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.uk/Games/Wii-U/The-Wonderful-101-641216.html |title=The Wonderful 101 |publisher=Nintendo |accessdate=July 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe single-player campaign is broken into levels. Each level ends with a grade depending on a number of factors, such as how long it takes the player to complete the level and how much damage was taken by the player. In addition to a single-player mode, the game has a cooperative mode that supports up to five players, with one person utilizing the [[Wii U GamePad]] and the four others each using their own [[Wii U Pro Controller]]s.<ref name=\"nintendolife2\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://e3.nintendo.com/games/detail/the-wonderful-101/ |title=The Wonderful 101 : Nintendo @ E3 2013 |website=E3.nintendo.com |accessdate=June 12, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614185211/http://e3.nintendo.com/games/detail/the-wonderful-101/ |archivedate=June 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nThe game takes place during a third war between Earth and an alien terrorist organization called the Geathjerk Federation that has invaded the planet. The only hope for humanity is the Wonderful Ones, a group of superheroes working for the CENTINELS Planetary Secret Service, an organization created by the United Nations.\n\n===Characters===\nThe main protagonists are Will Wedgewood (Wonder-Red), a Blossom City elementary school teacher and the leader of the Wonderful Ones, whose father Arthur is killed by Laambo; Eliot Hooker (Wonder-Blue), a police detective whose older brother is killed by Vijounne; guns expert Jean-Sebastain Renault (Wonder-Green); fashion modeler Mariana Kretzulesco (Wonder-Pink); Russian soldier Ivan Istochinkov (Wonder-Yellow); ninja-in-training Momoe Byakkoin (Wonder-White); and video game player Krishna Ramanujan (Wonder-Black).\n\nThe supporting characters are P-Star, a robot who assists the heroes; Laurence Nelson (Wonder-Captain), the commander of the CENTINELS who was previously known as Wonder-Red; Virgin Victory operator Alice MacGregor; and science chief James Shirogane. Luka Alan Smithee is a Blossom City Elementary School student whose scientist mother, Margarita, died working for the CENTINELS and gave her life so that the artificial intelligence, Mother Platinum, could sustain the Earth's defensive shield. Luka joins the group and becomes Wonder-Goggles at the end of the game. The last member of the Galactic Police Federation is Immorta; her brother, Prince Vorkken, lived at the Roaming Comet Rhullo, but was brainwashed by Gimme, an alien who plants a virus in the form of a bio-weapon insect named Vaaiki on Vorkken's body. Vorkken becomes the space pirate leader of the Guyzoch and sides with Chewgi. The main villain is Jergingha, the supreme overlord of the Geathjerk Federation, who is attempting to use Chi-Q to take back the galaxy from humanity.\n\n===Plot===\nThe story opens with a school bus full of children being attacked by alien invaders known as the Geathjerk. The teacher, Mr. Wedgewood, transforms into the superhero Wonder-Red and teams up with the other superheroes to destroy the aliens with Unite Morph powers. One student, however, Luka, appears disillusioned and expresses his hate for both the heroes and the aliens.\n\nThe heroes then meet on their flagship to plan their defences. The Earth is protected from invasion by a shield, powered by five Super Reactors. The heroes must travel around the world to protect these reactors and destroy the aliens who slip through the shield. As they travel, they meet up with Professor Shirogane, who explains that once the reactors are safe, they will use an orbiting cannon, the Shirogane Comet, to destroy the remainder of the aliens. Along the way, Wonder-Red struggles to lead his team, particularly Wonder-Blue, whose brother was killed by one of the alien leaders, Vijounne. Blue's desire for revenge causes several problems until Red convinces him to cooperate with the team. Also, Luka stows away on the ship and the heroes are forced to bring him along to keep him safe.\n\nThe heroes also repeatedly fight the space pirate Prince Vorkken and his first mate Chewgi. Vorkken is searching for the strongest fighters in the galaxy so that he can have the strength to get revenge on the Geathjerk. Vorkken fights with Unite Morph attacks similar to those of the heroes and serves as a [[Foil (literature)|foil]] to Wonder-Red in their encounters. With the help of Vorkken's sister, Immorta, the heroes defeat him, and Wonder-Red convinces Vorkken that his desire for revenge has turned him evil.\n\nAt the climax of the story, Luka betrays the heroes and joins the aliens, revealing that his pendant is the key that controls the Super Reactors. Luka explains that his mother died working on the shield that protects the Earth and he wants the aliens to destroy the Earth to get revenge for the loss of his mother. Wonder-Red however, announces that Luka's mother is still alive: she turned herself into Mother Platinum, the computer system that controls Earth's defences. Luka abandons his desire for revenge and Mother Platinum gathers pieces of the destroyed city to create a giant robot named \"Platinum Robo\". Using the robot, the heroes fight their way to the Shirogane Comet and fire its cannon, destroying the invading fleet. Jergingha, leader of the aliens, does not give up and returns in a gigantic fortress with an even bigger fleet. Platinum Robo flies to attack the fortress, while Chewgi and Vorkken arrive to help break through its defences. Upon being confronted, Jerrgingha reveals the Geathjerk are actually from 1,500 years in the future where Earth becomes an evil empire called the Greater Galactic Coelition, which has destroyed the homeworlds of the Geathjerk leaders. Geathjerk has come back in time to destroy Earth to prevent the Coelition from ever existing. Jergingha's fortress turns into a giant robot, even bigger than Platinum Robo, but the Wonderful Ones, Immorta, and Vorkken all combine their power and destroy it, saving the world. The Guyzoch leave with Vorkken to help rebuild the worlds they attacked. The Wonderful Ones vow to make sure Earth never becomes an Evil Empire like Jergingah seemingly predicted. Luka joins the Wonderful 100 to help make up for his mistakes. As a result, the team is renamed to the \"Wonderful 101\".\n\nThe epilogue shows Luka (now \"Wonder-Goggles\") and the other heroes saving a school bus from the aliens, paralleling the game's opening.  The story ends with the heroes continuing their fight against the remaining Geathjerk.\n\n==Development==\nThe development of what would become ''The Wonderful 101'' began during the lifetime of the [[Wii]]. The original idea came from PlatinumGames' president, Tatsuya Minami, who wanted to bring a group of popular or iconic video game characters together in one game. Because different gamers would prefer certain characters over others, the idea of being forced to play as a certain character at various points in the game was quickly scrapped. Instead, all of the characters would be on-screen at once so the player could choose between them at any time. PlatinumGames initially thought of using Nintendo first-party characters, who would work together to get past obstacles, but when the idea was presented to Nintendo, they questioned how the mechanic would fill an entire game. Director [[Hideki Kamiya]] also doubted that the \"conflicting elements\" of the different Nintendo characters could be successfully \"put into a consistent formula\" like in the ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]'' series. Further brainstorming was put on hold while he worked on another game, but when progress on that game was halted a year later, work on ''The Wonderful 101'' resumed. Kamiya decided to use the Japanese ''henshin'' / transforming theme, with a group of five original heroes who could unite and transform into various weapons. Soon the group expanded to one hundred heroes and the Japanese superhero style changed to \"an American comic book vibe\".\n\nThe game's design document was released by Platinum after stretch goals in the Kickstarter campaign for the remaster were met.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wonderful Wednesday #1: The Pitch Document |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/platinumgames/the-wonderful-101-remastered/posts/2747969 |website=[[Kickstarter]] |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |language=en |date=February 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Alistair |title=Hideki Kamiya Reveals The Wonderful 101 Design Document |url=https://www.siliconera.com/hideki-kamiya-reveals-the-wonderful-101-design-document/ |website=[[Siliconera]] |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |date=February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the developers had been thinking of making the game for the Wii, when PlatinumGames and Nintendo finalized their partnership, it became Wii U-exclusive. The developers wanted to use the console's unique features effectively, so they came up with drawing on the GamePad as a way to activate the \"Unite Morphs\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/wonderful-101-and-a-world-without-genres |title=Wonderful 101 and a World Without Genres |author=Parish, Jeremy |date=September 9, 2013 |website=US Gamer |accessdate=September 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909185557/http://www.usgamer.net/articles/wonderful-101-and-a-world-without-genres |archive-date=September 9, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videogamer.com/wiiu/the_wonderful_101/features/article/hideki_kamiya_interview_wonderful_101_the_bayonetta_2_controversy_his_twitter_account_and_more.html |title=Hideki Kamiya Interview: Wonderful 101, the Bayonetta 2 Controversy, His Twitter Account and More... |date=August 22, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060526/https://www.videogamer.com/wiiu/the_wonderful_101/features/article/hideki_kamiya_interview_wonderful_101_the_bayonetta_2_controversy_his_twitter_account_and_more.html |website=VideoGamer.com |publisher=Pro-G Media |accessdate=September 12, 2013  |archivedate=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{More citations needed|section|date=March 2020}}\nThe music in this game is an orchestrated score, written by Hiroshi Yamaguchi, Akira Takizawa, Hitomi Kurokawa, [[Norihiko Hibino]], Masato Kouda, and Rei Kondoh. The theme songs are called \"The Won-Stoppable Wonderful 100\" and \"The Won-Stoppable Wonderful 101\". They are sung by Foresta in the Japanese version and by Jimmy Wilcox, Rob McElroy, and Bruce Blanchard in the English version. A two-volume, official soundtrack was released on September 15, 2014. For ''Remastered'', [[Yoko Shimomura]], [[Keiichi Okabe]], and [[Yuzo Koshiro]] provided several arrangements.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Wonderful 101 will get remixed tracks from Yuzo Koshiro (Etrian Odyssey), Keiichi Okabe (Nier Automata), and Yoko Shimomura (Kingdom Hearts, Street Fighter, Mario & Luigi) (!!!) #AllFor101pic.twitter.com/7lUQvgc82Z |url=https://twitter.com/CartridgeGames/status/1235969062259343360 |website=@CartridgeGames |publisher=Twitter |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |language=en |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=June 2017}}\n''The Wonderful 101'' was revealed at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2012|E3 2012]] on the conference floor, codenamed ''Project P-100''. On July 3, 2013, Nintendo introduced their \"Wonderful Wednesday\" social networking campaign to promote ''The Wonderful 101'', where on each Wednesday leading up to the game's launch, they release a new character portrait. Two days later, however, Kamiya posted on [[Twitter]] that he was worried about the lack of marketing for ''The Wonderful 101''. He was referring to the lack of information in magazines or websites, and claimed that the game took almost 1.5 times the resources and manpower as Platinum's biggest game, ''[[Bayonetta]]''. During the August 7, 2013 [[List of Nintendo Direct presentations|Nintendo Direct]], [[Satoru Iwata]] announced that in two days time, a Nintendo Direct presentation would be made exclusively for ''The Wonderful 101''.\n\n===''Remastered''===\nIn a May 2018 interview, Kamiya stated that the team have some ideas for a possible port on the [[Nintendo Switch]], as he made internal documents on how they would do it.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sourcegaming.info/2018/05/15/straight-from-the-source-hideki-kamiya-and-atsushi-inaba-platinumgames/ |title=Straight from the Source: Hideki Kamiya and Atsushi Inaba (PlatinumGames) |author=Nirbion |date=May 13, 2018 |website=Source Gaming |accessdate=May 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516014953/https://sourcegaming.info/2018/05/15/straight-from-the-source-hideki-kamiya-and-atsushi-inaba-platinumgames/ |archive-date=May 16, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Platinum launched a [[Kickstarter]] in February 2020 to port the game in a remastered edition to the Switch and other platforms including [[personal computer]] and [[PlayStation 4]] when stretch goals were met, with further stretch goals to add [[downloadable content]] to the game.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Robson |first1=Daniel |title=PlatinumGames Celebrates Over $1 Million Pledged in Wonderful 101 Kickstarter (Update) |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/platinumgames-launches-wonderful-101-remastered-kickstarter-campaign |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203201344/https://www.ign.com/articles/platinumgames-launches-wonderful-101-remastered-kickstarter-campaign |archivedate=February 3, 2020 |language=en |date=February 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Wonderful 101: Remastered |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/platinumgames/the-wonderful-101-remastered/description |website=Kickstarter |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203211418/https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/platinumgames/the-wonderful-101-remastered/description |archivedate=February 3, 2020 |language=en |url-status=live}}</ref> Hideki Kamiya and [[Atsushi Inaba]] said that they had approached Nintendo, the publisher and co-owner of copyright and solely owner of trademark, about republishing the game for a wider audience. Nintendo only wanted to publish a new game if it was going to be exclusive to Nintendo Switch, while Platinum wanted the remaster to be on more platforms. Nintendo allowed them to do it, though they wouldn't publish the remaster. This gave Platinum the opportunity to try self-publishing. With the game nearly in a complete state for these new ports, they opted to use Kickstarter not only to judge how popular the game was, and thus mitigate the Kickstarter's stretch goals based on this, but also that there was still a necessary business element to self-publishing that the Kickstarter funds would help cover and deal with risks involved with publishing.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Robinson |first1=Andy |title=Interview: Platinum explains why it\u2019s crowdfunding The Wonderful 101 Remastered |url=https://www.videogameschronicle.com/features/interviews/wonderful-101-remastered/ |website=[[Video Games Chronicle]] |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203210210/https://www.videogameschronicle.com/features/interviews/wonderful-101-remastered/ |archivedate=February 3, 2020 |date=February 3, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Studio executive director Atsushi Inaba affirmed the Kickstarter was not about money for development but as a means to bring the community together and to make sure what additional content they could bring to the base game.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Taylor |first1=Haydn |title=PlatinumGames: The Wonderful 101 Kickstarter wasn't about the money |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2020-03-02-platinum-games-the-wonderful-101-kickstarter-wasnt-about-the-money |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |language=en |date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> Among other cosmetic updates, Platinum had devised a way to take the two-screen approach that had been used on the Wii U version (including the picture-in-picture) into a version that will work on the single-screen platforms. Drawing features will still be incorporated in the Switch version.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McWhertor |first1=Michael |title=What\u2019s changing in The Wonderful 101: Remastered |url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/2/3/21120978/wonderful-101-remastered-whats-changing-switch-port-ps4-pc |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |language=en |date=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWithin hours, the campaign had surpassed its goals for all three versions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Klepek |first1=Patrick |title=It Only Took Minutes for Fans to Crowdfund a 'Wonderful 101' Revival |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/n7j7b8/it-only-took-minutes-for-fans-to-crowdfund-a-wonderful-101-revival |website=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |language=en |date=February 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wales |first1=Matt |title=Wonderful 101: Remastered smashes Kickstarter goal in less than four hours |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2020-02-03-wonderful-101-remastered-smashes-kickstarter-goal-in-less-than-four-hours |website=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |language=en |date=February 3, 2020}}</ref> The campaign concluded with over {{USD|2.25 million}} raised, achieving several of the stretch goals that included a separate 2D side-scrolling game based on the adventures of Luka.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blake |first1=Vikki |title=Platinum Games adds new stretch goals as The Wonderful 101: Remastered Kickstarter exceeds $1.5m |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2020-02-09-platinum-games-adds-new-stretch-goals-as-the-wonderful-101-remastered-kickstarter-exceeds-usd1-5m |website=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=February 9, 2020 |language=en |date=February 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Valentine |first1=Rebekah |title=PlatinumGames raises over $2.2m for The Wonderful 101: Remastered |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2020-03-06-platinumgames-raises-over-USD2-2m-for-the-wonderful-101-remastered |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |language=en |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> A celebritory Twitch stream held by PlatinumGames on the Kickstarter's conclusion brought in additional donations that allowed a last stretch goal, orchestral arrangments of two of the game's songs, to be made as well.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Alistair |title=The Wonderful 101 Remastered Funds Orchestral Arrangements by End |url=https://www.siliconera.com/the-wonderful-101-remastered-kickstarter-finishes-with-orchestral-arrangement-funded |website=[[Siliconera]] |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> ''Remastered'' is planned for release in North America on May 19, 2020, in Europe on May 22, 2020, and in Japan on June 11, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Romano |first1=Sal |title=The Wonderful 101: Remastered launches May 19 in North America, May 22 in Europe, and June 11 in Japan |url=https://www.gematsu.com/2020/02/the-wonderful-101-remastered-launches-may-19-in-north-america-may-22-in-europe-and-june-11-in-japan |website=Gematsu |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n<!-- Aggregators -->\n| MC = 78/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/wii-u/the-wonderful-101 |title=The Wonderful 101 for Wii U Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710233541/http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii-u/the-wonderful-101 |archive-date=July 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| Destruct = 9/10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-the-wonderful-101-261553.phtml|publisher=Destructoid|accessdate=September 10, 2013|title=The Wonderful 101 review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130912214830/http://www.destructoid.com/review-the-wonderful-101-261553.phtml|archive-date=September 12, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Edge = 6/10\n| EGM = 7/10<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=September 10, 2013|publisher=EGM|url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/egm-review-the-wonderful-101/|title=Wonderful 101 for Wii U review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130912043035/http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/egm-review-the-wonderful-101/|archive-date=September 12, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| EuroG = 8/10<ref name=\"eurogamer1\">{{cite web |last=Stanton |first=Rich |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2013-08-18-the-wonderful-101-review |title=The Wonderful 101 review |website=EuroGamer |date=August 18, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170910220413/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2013-08-18-the-wonderful-101-review |archive-date=September 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Fam = 39/40<ref>{{cite web |last=Gifford |first=Kevin |date=August 21, 2013 |url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/8/21/4645134/japan-review-check-wonderful-101-lost-planet-3 |title=Japan Review Check: Wonderful 101, Lost Planet 3 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=August 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130827021139/http://www.polygon.com/2013/8/21/4645134/japan-review-check-wonderful-101-lost-planet-3 |archive-date=August 27, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=27598 |title=The Wonderful 101 |website=[[Famitsu]] |publisher=[[Enterbrain]] |accessdate=August 25, 2013 |language=ja |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130826145932/http://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=27598 |archive-date=August 26, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref name=\"gamespot1\">{{cite web |last=Gaston |first=Martin |url=http://www.gamespot.com/the-wonderful-101/reviews/the-wonderful-101-review-6413062/?tag=Topslot;Slot2 |title=The Wonderful 101 Review |website=GameSpot |date=August 18, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214120325/https://www.gamespot.com/the-wonderful-101/reviews/the-wonderful-101-review-6413062/?tag=Topslot%3BSlot2 |archive-date=December 14, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/the-wonderful-101-review/|title=Wonderful 101 for Wii U review|accessdate=August 18, 2013|publisher=GamesRadar+|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140123004600/http://www.gamesradar.com/the-wonderful-101-review/|archive-date=January 23, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| GTM = 7/10\n| GI = 7.5/10<ref>{{cite web|title=Wonderful 101 review|accessdate=September 10, 2013|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/the_wonderful_101/b/wii_u/archive/2013/09/10/wonderful-101-review-game-informer.aspx|publisher=Game Informer|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130912045636/http://www.gameinformer.com/games/the_wonderful_101/b/wii_u/archive/2013/09/10/wonderful-101-review-game-informer.aspx|archive-date=September 12, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| IGN = 7.4/10<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web |author=Keza Macdonald |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/08/18/the-wonderful-101-review |title=The Wonderful 101 Review |website=IGN |date=August 18, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712082858/http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/08/18/the-wonderful-101-review |archive-date=July 12, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Joystiq = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"joystiq1\">{{cite web|last1=Martin|first1=Garrett|title=The Wonderful 101 review: Barrel of superheroes|url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/09/10/the-wonderful-101-review/|website=Engadget|accessdate=October 8, 2017|date=October 9, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008081650/https://www.engadget.com/2013/09/10/the-wonderful-101-review/|archive-date=October 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| NWR = 9/10<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Nintendo World Report|accessdate=September 10, 2013|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/35385/the-wonderful-101-wii-u|title=The Wonderful 101 review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219085549/http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/35385/the-wonderful-101-wii-u|archive-date=February 19, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| NLife = 9/10<ref name=\"nintendolife1\">{{cite web |last=Whitehead |first=Thomas |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/wiiu/wonderful_101 |title=The Wonderful 101 Review - Wii U |website=Nintendo Life |date=August 18, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710152211/http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/wiiu/wonderful_101 |archive-date=July 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| ONM = 93%\n| VG = 8/10<ref name=\"videogamer1\">{{cite web|last1=Cairns|first1=Daniel|title=The Wonderful 101 Review|url=https://www.videogamer.com/reviews/the-wonderful-101-review|website=VideoGamer.com|accessdate=July 7, 2017|date=August 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008080553/https://www.videogamer.com/reviews/the-wonderful-101-review|archive-date=October 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''The Wonderful 101'' received generally positive reviews from critics. It has an aggregate score of 78/100 on [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MC\" /> The game came in for criticism from some game reviewers over its hard learning curve, while others, such as Nintendo Enthusiast's Michael Nelson, praised the game for requiring a certain amount of skill.<ref>{{cite web |last=Nelson |first=Michael |url=http://nintendoenthusiast.com/review/review-wonderful-101/ |title=The Wonderful 101 Review for Wii U |website=Nintendo Enthusiast |date=September 12, 2013 |accessdate=June 11, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304022642/http://nintendoenthusiast.com/review/review-wonderful-101/ |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nMost reviewers enjoyed the ridiculously nonsensical story, characters, and humor, but some found the few sexual jokes in the game to be out-of-place in what was perceived as a kid-friendly game (although it has a Teen rating).<ref name=\"eurogamer1\"/><ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/><ref name=\"joystiq1\"/><ref name=\"archive1\">{{cite web|last1=Holmes|first1=Jonathan|title=Review: The Wonderful 101|url=http://www.destructoid.com/review-the-wonderful-101-261553.phtml|website=Destructoid|publisher=Wayback Machine|accessdate=July 7, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926072225/http://www.destructoid.com/review-the-wonderful-101-261553.phtml|archivedate=September 26, 2013|date=October 9, 2013}}</ref> ''The Wonderful 101''{{'}}s length and pacing seemed a bit drawn-out to some reviewers due to repetitive enemies and [[Boss (video gaming)|boss]] fights,<ref name=\"gamespot1\"/><ref name=\"videogamer1\"/><ref name=\"gamesradar\">{{cite web |last=Bradford |first=Matt |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/the-wonderful-101-review/ |title=The Wonderful 101 review |website=GamesRadar+ |date=September 11, 2014 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707112505/http://www.gamesradar.com/the-wonderful-101-review/ |archive-date=July 7, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> while others thought these issues were unproblematic thanks to the even distribution of new moves and upgrades.<ref name=\"eurogamer1\"/><ref name=\"nintendolife1\"/>\n\nThe necessity of forming weapons by drawing on the touchscreen garnered a mixed reception. Many reviewers found that the GamePad worked fine for straight lines or circles (to make a sword or a fist), but that it sometimes interpreted more complex shapes as the wrong weapon.<ref name=\"eurogamer1\"/><ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/><ref name=\"gamesradar\"/> Others thought that drawing simple shapes on the GamePad while using the right analogue stick for others was more reliable,<ref name=\"gamespot1\"/> or that the GamePad worked perfectly and it was simply a matter of practice.<ref name=\"nintendolife1\"/><ref name=\"archive1\"/> The camera was criticized for being too zoomed-out to keep track of all of the characters during battle but also too zoomed-in to see the occasional out-of-view enemy.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/><ref name=\"joystiq1\"/><ref name=\"gamesradar\"/> Reviewers agreed that the game lived up to PlatinumGames' trademark high difficulty, with some citing the controls and camera as contributing factors.<ref name=\"gamesradar\"/>\n\nNearly all critics were pleased with the creative uses of the GamePad's second screen.<ref name=\"gamespot1\"/><ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/><ref name=\"gamesradar\"/> However, a few thought that navigating inside of a building using the controller's [[gyroscope]] was clunky.<ref name=\"nintendolife1\"/> Many also thought the multiplayer mode was enjoyable, but often lost track of their own group of characters. Most agreed that it felt \"tacked on\".<ref name=\"gamespot1\"/><ref name=\"archive1\"/> ''The Wonderful 101''{{'s}} cartoony art style and flashy effects in battle were also praised.<ref name=\"eurogamer1\"/><ref name=\"nintendolife1\"/> The set-pieces and giant bosses were likewise well-received, as were the voice acting and soundtrack.<ref name=\"eurogamer1\"/><ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>\n\n===Sales===\nNintendo shipped 30,000 copies for the game's launch in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Ishann|title=The Wonderful 101 Will Launch With Just 30,000 Copies In Japan|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2013/08/19/the-wonderful-101-will-launch-with-just-30000-copies-in-japan|website=Siliconera|accessdate=June 14, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626001401/http://www.siliconera.com/2013/08/19/the-wonderful-101-will-launch-with-just-30000-copies-in-japan|archivedate=June 26, 2014|date=August 19, 2013}}</ref> The game sold 5,258 copies in its first week in Japan<ref name=\"videogamer2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.videogamer.com/wiiu/the_wonderful_101/news/the_wonderful_101_slows_down_wii_u_sales_in_japan.html |title=The Wonderful 101 slows down Wii U sales in Japan |website=VideoGamer.com |date=August 28, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041902/http://www.videogamer.com/wiiu/the_wonderful_101/news/the_wonderful_101_slows_down_wii_u_sales_in_japan.html |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> and reached 22nd place in its first week of the UK sales chart.<ref name=\"videogamer2\"/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Legacy==\nBoth Atsushi Inaba and Hideki Kamiya have expressed interest in a sequel.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Doolan |first1=Liam |title=PlatinumGames Open To Wonderful 101 Sequel, As Long As Fans Show Their Support |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2020/02/platinumgames_open_to_wonderful_101_sequel_as_long_as_fans_show_their_support |website=[[Nintendo Life]] |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |date=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe seven main protagonists appeared as Trophies in ''[[Super Smash Bros. for Wii U]]'', and Wonder-Red and Wonder-Blue appeared as Spirits in ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]''.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://thewonderful101.nintendo.com/}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.platinumgames.com/games/the-wonderful-101|''Remastered'' official website}}\n\n{{Hideki Kamiya}}\n{{PlatinumGames}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wonderful 101, The}}\n[[Category:2013 video games]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n[[Category:Alien invasions in video games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Wii games]]\n[[Category:Cooperative video games]]\n[[Category:Hack and slash games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Network games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch eShop games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n[[Category:PlatinumGames games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 Pro enhanced games]]\n[[Category:Superhero video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games directed by Hideki Kamiya]]\n[[Category:Wii U eShop games]]\n[[Category:Wii U games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = The Wonderful 101\n| image = Wonderful 101 box artwork.jpg\n| caption = North American Wii U box art\n| developer = [[PlatinumGames]]\n| publisher = {{ubl|[[Nintendo]] (Wii U)|PlatinumGames (NS, Win, PS4)}}\n| director = [[Hideki Kamiya]]\n| producer = {{ubl|[[Atsushi Inaba]]|Hitoshi Yamagami}}\n| designer = Hiroshi Shibata\n| programmer =\n| artist = {{ubl|Yuka Kotaki|Ryo Koizumi}}\n| writer = Hideki Kamiya\n| composer = {{ubl|[[Norihiko Hibino]]|Hiroshi Yamaguchi|Rei Kondoh|Akira Takizawa|Hitomi Kurokawa|Masato Kouda}}\n| platforms = [[Wii U]], [[Nintendo Switch]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]]\n| released = '''Wii U'''{{vgrelease|EU|August 23, 2013<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |last=Karmali |first=Luke |url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2013/05/17/the-wonderful-101-release-date-announced |title=The Wonderful 101 Release Date Announced |website=IGN |date=May 17, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Hzl7kVZV?url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/05/17/the-wonderful-101-release-date-announced |archive-date=July 10, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>|[[Japan|JP]]/[[Australasia|AU]]|August 24, 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.com.au/index.php?action=news&nid=2903&pageID=6|title=NINTENDO ANNOUNCES EXCLUSIVE WORLDWIDE PARTNERSHIP WITH SEGA FOR UPCOMING SONIC THE HEDGEHOG GAMES|publisher=Nintendo Australia Pty. Ltd.|date=May 18, 2013|accessdate=May 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908051626/http://www.nintendo.com.au/index.php?action=news&nid=2903&pageID=6|archive-date=September 8, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>|NA|September 15, 2013<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>}}\n'''Switch, Windows, PS4'''{{vgrelease|NA|May 19, 2020|EU|May 22, 2020|JP|June 11, 2020}}\n| genre = [[Action-adventure]], [[hack and slash]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n{{nihongo foot|'''''The Wonderful 101'''''|\u30b6\u30fb\u30ef\u30f3\u30c0\u30d5\u30eb \u30ef\u30f3\u30fb\u30aa\u30fc\u30fb\u30ef\u30f3|Za Wandafuru Wan \u014c Wan|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is an [[action-adventure game]] developed by [[PlatinumGames]] and published by [[Nintendo]] for the [[Wii U]]. The game was directed by [[Hideki Kamiya]] and produced by [[Atsushi Inaba]]; the pair also worked together on the ''[[Viewtiful Joe]]'' series and ''[[\u014ckami]]''. It was released in August 2013 in all major regions except North America, where it released the following month. ''The Wonderful 101'' received generally positive reviews, but failed to meet sales expectations.\n\nIn February 2020, PlatinumGames announced a remastered version for [[Nintendo Switch]], [[Microsoft Windows]] and [[PlayStation 4]], financed through [[crowdfunding]], with a planned release in May 2020.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:The Wonderful 101 Unite Morph battle screenshot.png|thumb|Screenshot of an earlier version of the game depicting a \"Unite Morph\" ability used to battle an opponent. The heroes have combined to form \"Unite Hand\", which is shown punching a large enemy called the Diedough-Goo.]]\n\nIn ''The Wonderful 101'', players control a horde of superheroes from an [[Isometric graphics in video games and pixel art|isometric]] viewpoint and can turn them into various objects called \"Unite Morphs.\" As levels progress, players must explore each stage to find helpless citizens and recruit them to join their army of heroes. The more heroes gathered, the greater the special morph powers can be. At the cost of depleting their battery meter, players can use \"Unite Morph\" forms to defeat enemies, solve puzzles, or traverse the environment. The meter can be recharged by performing normal attacks or by picking up batteries dropped by a defeated enemy. Enemies will also drop \"O parts\" (the in-game currency used to buy upgrades), new \"Unite Morph\" abilities and items. To transform the horde of heroes, the appropriate symbol is drawn on the [[Wii U GamePad]]'s touchscreen or right [[analog stick]], such as an \u201cL\u201d for a gun or a squiggly line for a whip. In specified areas, the GamePad (by default) is used to change the view to a traditional, third-person angle and better explore tighter environments, such as those found indoors and inside caves.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://e3.nintendo.com/games/#/wiiu/projectp-100 |title=Nintendo All-Access @ E3 2012 - Games |website=E3.nintendo.com |accessdate=July 9, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120920061728/http://e3.nintendo.com/games/#/wiiu/projectp-100 |archivedate=September 20, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"nintendolife2\">{{cite web |last=Meyer |first=Lee |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2013/06/hands_on_the_wonderful_101/ |title=Hands On: The Wonderful 101 |work=Nintendo Life |date=June 26, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920093231/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2013/06/hands_on_the_wonderful_101 |archive-date=September 20, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.uk/Games/Wii-U/The-Wonderful-101-641216.html |title=The Wonderful 101 |publisher=Nintendo |accessdate=July 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe single-player campaign is broken into levels. Each level ends with a grade depending on a number of factors, such as how long it takes the player to complete the level and how much damage was taken by the player. In addition to a single-player mode, the game has a cooperative mode that supports up to five players, with one person utilizing the [[Wii U GamePad]] and the four others each using their own [[Wii U Pro Controller]]s.<ref name=\"nintendolife2\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://e3.nintendo.com/games/detail/the-wonderful-101/ |title=The Wonderful 101 : Nintendo @ E3 2013 |website=E3.nintendo.com |accessdate=June 12, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614185211/http://e3.nintendo.com/games/detail/the-wonderful-101/ |archivedate=June 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nThe game takes place during a third war between Earth and an alien terrorist organization called the Geathjerk Federation that has invaded the planet. The only hope for humanity is the Wonderful Ones, a group of superheroes working for the CENTINELS Planetary Secret Service, an organization created by the United Nations.\n\n===Characters===\nThe main protagonists are Will Wedgewood (Wonder-Red), a Blossom City elementary school teacher and the leader of the Wonderful Ones, whose father Arthur is killed by Laambo; Eliot Hooker (Wonder-Blue), a police detective whose older brother is killed by Vijounne; guns expert Jean-Sebastain Renault (Wonder-Green); fashion modeler Mariana Kretzulesco (Wonder-Pink); Russian soldier Ivan Istochinkov (Wonder-Yellow); ninja-in-training Momoe Byakkoin (Wonder-White); and video game player Krishna Ramanujan (Wonder-Black).\n\nThe supporting characters are P-Star, a robot who assists the heroes; Laurence Nelson (Wonder-Captain), the commander of the CENTINELS who was previously known as Wonder-Red; Virgin Victory operator Alice MacGregor; and science chief James Shirogane. Luka Alan Smithee is a Blossom City Elementary School student whose scientist mother, Margarita, died working for the CENTINELS and gave her life so that the artificial intelligence, Mother Platinum, could sustain the Earth's defensive shield. Luka joins the group and becomes Wonder-Goggles at the end of the game. The last member of the Galactic Police Federation is Immorta; her brother, Prince Vorkken, lived at the Roaming Comet Rhullo, but was brainwashed by Gimme, an alien who plants a virus in the form of a bio-weapon insect named Vaaiki on Vorkken's body. Vorkken becomes the space pirate leader of the Guyzoch and sides with Chewgi. The main villain is Jergingha, the supreme overlord of the Geathjerk Federation, who is attempting to use Chi-Q to take back the galaxy from humanity.\n\n===Plot===\nThe story opens with a school bus full of children being attacked by alien invaders known as the Geathjerk. The teacher, Mr. Wedgewood, transforms into the superhero Wonder-Red and teams up with the other superheroes to destroy the aliens with Unite Morph powers. One student, however, Luka, appears disillusioned and expresses his hate for both the heroes and the aliens.\n\nThe heroes then meet on their flagship to plan their defences. The Earth is protected from invasion by a shield, powered by five Super Reactors. The heroes must travel around the world to protect these reactors and destroy the aliens who slip through the shield. As they travel, they meet up with Professor Shirogane, who explains that once the reactors are safe, they will use an orbiting cannon, the Shirogane Comet, to destroy the remainder of the aliens. Along the way, Wonder-Red struggles to lead his team, particularly Wonder-Blue, whose brother was killed by one of the alien leaders, Vijounne. Blue's desire for revenge causes several problems until Red convinces him to cooperate with the team. Also, Luka stows away on the ship and the heroes are forced to bring him along to keep him safe.\n\nThe heroes also repeatedly fight the space pirate Prince Vorkken and his first mate Chewgi. Vorkken is searching for the strongest fighters in the galaxy so that he can have the strength to get revenge on the Geathjerk. Vorkken fights with Unite Morph attacks similar to those of the heroes and serves as a [[Foil (literature)|foil]] to Wonder-Red in their encounters. With the help of Vorkken's sister, Immorta, the heroes defeat him, and Wonder-Red convinces Vorkken that his desire for revenge has turned him evil.\n\nAt the climax of the story, Luka betrays the heroes and joins the aliens, revealing that his pendant is the key that controls the Super Reactors. Luka explains that his mother died working on the shield that protects the Earth and he wants the aliens to destroy the Earth to get revenge for the loss of his mother. Wonder-Red however, announces that Luka's mother is still alive: she turned herself into Mother Platinum, the computer system that controls Earth's defences. Luka abandons his desire for revenge and Mother Platinum gathers pieces of the destroyed city to create a giant robot named \"Platinum Robo\". Using the robot, the heroes fight their way to the Shirogane Comet and fire its cannon, destroying the invading fleet. Jergingha, leader of the aliens, does not give up and returns in a gigantic fortress with an even bigger fleet. Platinum Robo flies to attack the fortress, while Chewgi and Vorkken arrive to help break through its defences. Upon being confronted, Jerrgingha reveals the Geathjerk are actually from 1,500 years in the future where Earth becomes an evil empire called the Greater Galactic Coelition, which has destroyed the homeworlds of the Geathjerk leaders. Geathjerk has come back in time to destroy Earth to prevent the Coelition from ever existing. Jergingha's fortress turns into a giant robot, even bigger than Platinum Robo, but the Wonderful Ones, Immorta, and Vorkken all combine their power and destroy it, saving the world. The Guyzoch leave with Vorkken to help rebuild the worlds they attacked. The Wonderful Ones vow to make sure Earth never becomes an Evil Empire like Jergingah seemingly predicted. Luka joins the Wonderful 100 to help make up for his mistakes. As a result, the team is renamed to the \"Wonderful 101\".\n\nThe epilogue shows Luka (now \"Wonder-Goggles\") and the other heroes saving a school bus from the aliens, paralleling the game's opening.  The story ends with the heroes continuing their fight against the remaining Geathjerk.\n\n==Development==\nThe development of what would become ''The Wonderful 101'' began during the lifetime of the [[Wii]]. The original idea came from PlatinumGames' president, Tatsuya Minami, who wanted to bring a group of popular or iconic video game characters together in one game. Because different gamers would prefer certain characters over others, the idea of being forced to play as a certain character at various points in the game was quickly scrapped. Instead, all of the characters would be on-screen at once so the player could choose between them at any time. PlatinumGames initially thought of using Nintendo first-party characters, who would work together to get past obstacles, but when the idea was presented to Nintendo, they questioned how the mechanic would fill an entire game. Director [[Hideki Kamiya]] also doubted that the \"conflicting elements\" of the different Nintendo characters could be successfully \"put into a consistent formula\" like in the ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]'' series. Further brainstorming was put on hold while he worked on another game, but when progress on that game was halted a year later, work on ''The Wonderful 101'' resumed. Kamiya decided to use the Japanese ''henshin'' / transforming theme, with a group of five original heroes who could unite and transform into various weapons. Soon the group expanded to one hundred heroes and the Japanese superhero style changed to \"an American comic book vibe\".\n\nThe game's design document was released by Platinum after stretch goals in the Kickstarter campaign for the remaster were met.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wonderful Wednesday #1: The Pitch Document |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/platinumgames/the-wonderful-101-remastered/posts/2747969 |website=[[Kickstarter]] |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |language=en |date=February 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Alistair |title=Hideki Kamiya Reveals The Wonderful 101 Design Document |url=https://www.siliconera.com/hideki-kamiya-reveals-the-wonderful-101-design-document/ |website=[[Siliconera]] |accessdate=February 5, 2020 |date=February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the developers had been thinking of making the game for the Wii, when PlatinumGames and Nintendo finalized their partnership, it became Wii U-exclusive. The developers wanted to use the console's unique features effectively, so they came up with drawing on the GamePad as a way to activate the \"Unite Morphs\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/wonderful-101-and-a-world-without-genres |title=Wonderful 101 and a World Without Genres |author=Parish, Jeremy |date=September 9, 2013 |website=US Gamer |accessdate=September 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909185557/http://www.usgamer.net/articles/wonderful-101-and-a-world-without-genres |archive-date=September 9, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videogamer.com/wiiu/the_wonderful_101/features/article/hideki_kamiya_interview_wonderful_101_the_bayonetta_2_controversy_his_twitter_account_and_more.html |title=Hideki Kamiya Interview: Wonderful 101, the Bayonetta 2 Controversy, His Twitter Account and More... |date=August 22, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060526/https://www.videogamer.com/wiiu/the_wonderful_101/features/article/hideki_kamiya_interview_wonderful_101_the_bayonetta_2_controversy_his_twitter_account_and_more.html |website=VideoGamer.com |publisher=Pro-G Media |accessdate=September 12, 2013  |archivedate=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{More citations needed|section|date=March 2020}}\nThe music in this game is an orchestrated score, written by Hiroshi Yamaguchi, Akira Takizawa, Hitomi Kurokawa, [[Norihiko Hibino]], Masato Kouda, and Rei Kondoh. The theme songs are called \"The Won-Stoppable Wonderful 100\" and \"The Won-Stoppable Wonderful 101\". They are sung by Foresta in the Japanese version and by Jimmy Wilcox, Rob McElroy, and Bruce Blanchard in the English version. A two-volume, official soundtrack was released on September 15, 2014. For ''Remastered'', [[Yoko Shimomura]], [[Keiichi Okabe]], and [[Yuzo Koshiro]] provided several arrangements.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Wonderful 101 will get remixed tracks from Yuzo Koshiro (Etrian Odyssey), Keiichi Okabe (Nier Automata), and Yoko Shimomura (Kingdom Hearts, Street Fighter, Mario & Luigi) (!!!) #AllFor101pic.twitter.com/7lUQvgc82Z |url=https://twitter.com/CartridgeGames/status/1235969062259343360 |website=@CartridgeGames |publisher=Twitter |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |language=en |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=June 2017}}\n''The Wonderful 101'' was revealed at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2012|E3 2012]] on the conference floor, codenamed ''Project P-100''. On July 3, 2013, Nintendo introduced their \"Wonderful Wednesday\" social networking campaign to promote ''The Wonderful 101'', where on each Wednesday leading up to the game's launch, they release a new character portrait. Two days later, however, Kamiya posted on [[Twitter]] that he was worried about the lack of marketing for ''The Wonderful 101''. He was referring to the lack of information in magazines or websites, and claimed that the game took almost 1.5 times the resources and manpower as Platinum's biggest game, ''[[Bayonetta]]''. During the August 7, 2013 [[List of Nintendo Direct presentations|Nintendo Direct]], [[Satoru Iwata]] announced that in two days time, a Nintendo Direct presentation would be made exclusively for ''The Wonderful 101''.\n\n===''Remastered''===\nIn a May 2018 interview, Kamiya stated that the team have some ideas for a possible port on the [[Nintendo Switch]], as he made internal documents on how they would do it.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sourcegaming.info/2018/05/15/straight-from-the-source-hideki-kamiya-and-atsushi-inaba-platinumgames/ |title=Straight from the Source: Hideki Kamiya and Atsushi Inaba (PlatinumGames) |author=Nirbion |date=May 13, 2018 |website=Source Gaming |accessdate=May 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516014953/https://sourcegaming.info/2018/05/15/straight-from-the-source-hideki-kamiya-and-atsushi-inaba-platinumgames/ |archive-date=May 16, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Platinum launched a [[Kickstarter]] in February 2020 to port the game in a remastered edition to the Switch and other platforms including [[personal computer]] and [[PlayStation 4]] when stretch goals were met, with further stretch goals to add [[downloadable content]] to the game.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Robson |first1=Daniel |title=PlatinumGames Celebrates Over $1 Million Pledged in Wonderful 101 Kickstarter (Update) |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/platinumgames-launches-wonderful-101-remastered-kickstarter-campaign |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203201344/https://www.ign.com/articles/platinumgames-launches-wonderful-101-remastered-kickstarter-campaign |archivedate=February 3, 2020 |language=en |date=February 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Wonderful 101: Remastered |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/platinumgames/the-wonderful-101-remastered/description |website=Kickstarter |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203211418/https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/platinumgames/the-wonderful-101-remastered/description |archivedate=February 3, 2020 |language=en |url-status=live}}</ref> Hideki Kamiya and [[Atsushi Inaba]] said that they had approached Nintendo, the publisher and co-owner of copyright and solely owner of trademark, about republishing the game for a wider audience. Nintendo only wanted to publish a new game if it was going to be exclusive to Nintendo Switch, while Platinum wanted the remaster to be on more platforms. Nintendo allowed them to do it, though they wouldn't publish the remaster. This gave Platinum the opportunity to try self-publishing. With the game nearly in a complete state for these new ports, they opted to use Kickstarter not only to judge how popular the game was, and thus mitigate the Kickstarter's stretch goals based on this, but also that there was still a necessary business element to self-publishing that the Kickstarter funds would help cover and deal with risks involved with publishing.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Robinson |first1=Andy |title=Interview: Platinum explains why it\u2019s crowdfunding The Wonderful 101 Remastered |url=https://www.videogameschronicle.com/features/interviews/wonderful-101-remastered/ |website=[[Video Games Chronicle]] |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203210210/https://www.videogameschronicle.com/features/interviews/wonderful-101-remastered/ |archivedate=February 3, 2020 |date=February 3, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Studio executive director Atsushi Inaba affirmed the Kickstarter was not about money for development but as a means to bring the community together and to make sure what additional content they could bring to the base game.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Taylor |first1=Haydn |title=PlatinumGames: The Wonderful 101 Kickstarter wasn't about the money |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2020-03-02-platinum-games-the-wonderful-101-kickstarter-wasnt-about-the-money |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |language=en |date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> Among other cosmetic updates, Platinum had devised a way to take the two-screen approach that had been used on the Wii U version (including the picture-in-picture) into a version that will work on the single-screen platforms. Drawing features will still be incorporated in the Switch version.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McWhertor |first1=Michael |title=What\u2019s changing in The Wonderful 101: Remastered |url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/2/3/21120978/wonderful-101-remastered-whats-changing-switch-port-ps4-pc |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |language=en |date=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWithin hours, the campaign had surpassed its goals for all three versions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Klepek |first1=Patrick |title=It Only Took Minutes for Fans to Crowdfund a 'Wonderful 101' Revival |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/n7j7b8/it-only-took-minutes-for-fans-to-crowdfund-a-wonderful-101-revival |website=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |language=en |date=February 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wales |first1=Matt |title=Wonderful 101: Remastered smashes Kickstarter goal in less than four hours |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2020-02-03-wonderful-101-remastered-smashes-kickstarter-goal-in-less-than-four-hours |website=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |language=en |date=February 3, 2020}}</ref> The campaign concluded with over {{USD|2.2 million}} raised, achieving several of the stretch goals that included a separate 2D side-scrolling game based on the adventures of Luka.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blake |first1=Vikki |title=Platinum Games adds new stretch goals as The Wonderful 101: Remastered Kickstarter exceeds $1.5m |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2020-02-09-platinum-games-adds-new-stretch-goals-as-the-wonderful-101-remastered-kickstarter-exceeds-usd1-5m |website=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=February 9, 2020 |language=en |date=February 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Valentine |first1=Rebekah |title=PlatinumGames raises over $2.2m for The Wonderful 101: Remastered |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2020-03-06-platinumgames-raises-over-USD2-2m-for-the-wonderful-101-remastered |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |language=en |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> A celebritory Twitch stream held by PlatinumGames on the Kickstarter's conclusion brought in additional donations that allowed a last stretch goal, orchestral arrangments of two of the game's songs, to be made as well.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Alistair |title=The Wonderful 101 Remastered Funds Orchestral Arrangements by End |url=https://www.siliconera.com/the-wonderful-101-remastered-kickstarter-finishes-with-orchestral-arrangement-funded |website=[[Siliconera]] |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> ''Remastered'' is planned for release in North America on May 19, 2020, in Europe on May 22, 2020, and in Japan on June 11, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Romano |first1=Sal |title=The Wonderful 101: Remastered launches May 19 in North America, May 22 in Europe, and June 11 in Japan |url=https://www.gematsu.com/2020/02/the-wonderful-101-remastered-launches-may-19-in-north-america-may-22-in-europe-and-june-11-in-japan |website=Gematsu |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n<!-- Aggregators -->\n| MC = 78/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/wii-u/the-wonderful-101 |title=The Wonderful 101 for Wii U Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710233541/http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii-u/the-wonderful-101 |archive-date=July 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| Destruct = 9/10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-the-wonderful-101-261553.phtml|publisher=Destructoid|accessdate=September 10, 2013|title=The Wonderful 101 review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130912214830/http://www.destructoid.com/review-the-wonderful-101-261553.phtml|archive-date=September 12, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Edge = 6/10\n| EGM = 7/10<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=September 10, 2013|publisher=EGM|url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/egm-review-the-wonderful-101/|title=Wonderful 101 for Wii U review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130912043035/http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/egm-review-the-wonderful-101/|archive-date=September 12, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| EuroG = 8/10<ref name=\"eurogamer1\">{{cite web |last=Stanton |first=Rich |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2013-08-18-the-wonderful-101-review |title=The Wonderful 101 review |website=EuroGamer |date=August 18, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170910220413/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2013-08-18-the-wonderful-101-review |archive-date=September 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Fam = 39/40<ref>{{cite web |last=Gifford |first=Kevin |date=August 21, 2013 |url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/8/21/4645134/japan-review-check-wonderful-101-lost-planet-3 |title=Japan Review Check: Wonderful 101, Lost Planet 3 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=August 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130827021139/http://www.polygon.com/2013/8/21/4645134/japan-review-check-wonderful-101-lost-planet-3 |archive-date=August 27, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=27598 |title=The Wonderful 101 |website=[[Famitsu]] |publisher=[[Enterbrain]] |accessdate=August 25, 2013 |language=ja |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130826145932/http://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=27598 |archive-date=August 26, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref name=\"gamespot1\">{{cite web |last=Gaston |first=Martin |url=http://www.gamespot.com/the-wonderful-101/reviews/the-wonderful-101-review-6413062/?tag=Topslot;Slot2 |title=The Wonderful 101 Review |website=GameSpot |date=August 18, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214120325/https://www.gamespot.com/the-wonderful-101/reviews/the-wonderful-101-review-6413062/?tag=Topslot%3BSlot2 |archive-date=December 14, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/the-wonderful-101-review/|title=Wonderful 101 for Wii U review|accessdate=August 18, 2013|publisher=GamesRadar+|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140123004600/http://www.gamesradar.com/the-wonderful-101-review/|archive-date=January 23, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| GTM = 7/10\n| GI = 7.5/10<ref>{{cite web|title=Wonderful 101 review|accessdate=September 10, 2013|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/the_wonderful_101/b/wii_u/archive/2013/09/10/wonderful-101-review-game-informer.aspx|publisher=Game Informer|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130912045636/http://www.gameinformer.com/games/the_wonderful_101/b/wii_u/archive/2013/09/10/wonderful-101-review-game-informer.aspx|archive-date=September 12, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| IGN = 7.4/10<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web |author=Keza Macdonald |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/08/18/the-wonderful-101-review |title=The Wonderful 101 Review |website=IGN |date=August 18, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712082858/http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/08/18/the-wonderful-101-review |archive-date=July 12, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Joystiq = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"joystiq1\">{{cite web|last1=Martin|first1=Garrett|title=The Wonderful 101 review: Barrel of superheroes|url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/09/10/the-wonderful-101-review/|website=Engadget|accessdate=October 8, 2017|date=October 9, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008081650/https://www.engadget.com/2013/09/10/the-wonderful-101-review/|archive-date=October 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| NWR = 9/10<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Nintendo World Report|accessdate=September 10, 2013|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/35385/the-wonderful-101-wii-u|title=The Wonderful 101 review|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219085549/http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/35385/the-wonderful-101-wii-u|archive-date=February 19, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| NLife = 9/10<ref name=\"nintendolife1\">{{cite web |last=Whitehead |first=Thomas |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/wiiu/wonderful_101 |title=The Wonderful 101 Review - Wii U |website=Nintendo Life |date=August 18, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710152211/http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/wiiu/wonderful_101 |archive-date=July 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| ONM = 93%\n| VG = 8/10<ref name=\"videogamer1\">{{cite web|last1=Cairns|first1=Daniel|title=The Wonderful 101 Review|url=https://www.videogamer.com/reviews/the-wonderful-101-review|website=VideoGamer.com|accessdate=July 7, 2017|date=August 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008080553/https://www.videogamer.com/reviews/the-wonderful-101-review|archive-date=October 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''The Wonderful 101'' received generally positive reviews from critics. It has an aggregate score of 78/100 on [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MC\" /> The game came in for criticism from some game reviewers over its hard learning curve, while others, such as Nintendo Enthusiast's Michael Nelson, praised the game for requiring a certain amount of skill.<ref>{{cite web |last=Nelson |first=Michael |url=http://nintendoenthusiast.com/review/review-wonderful-101/ |title=The Wonderful 101 Review for Wii U |website=Nintendo Enthusiast |date=September 12, 2013 |accessdate=June 11, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304022642/http://nintendoenthusiast.com/review/review-wonderful-101/ |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nMost reviewers enjoyed the ridiculously nonsensical story, characters, and humor, but some found the few sexual jokes in the game to be out-of-place in what was perceived as a kid-friendly game (although it has a Teen rating).<ref name=\"eurogamer1\"/><ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/><ref name=\"joystiq1\"/><ref name=\"archive1\">{{cite web|last1=Holmes|first1=Jonathan|title=Review: The Wonderful 101|url=http://www.destructoid.com/review-the-wonderful-101-261553.phtml|website=Destructoid|publisher=Wayback Machine|accessdate=July 7, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926072225/http://www.destructoid.com/review-the-wonderful-101-261553.phtml|archivedate=September 26, 2013|date=October 9, 2013}}</ref> ''The Wonderful 101''{{'}}s length and pacing seemed a bit drawn-out to some reviewers due to repetitive enemies and [[Boss (video gaming)|boss]] fights,<ref name=\"gamespot1\"/><ref name=\"videogamer1\"/><ref name=\"gamesradar\">{{cite web |last=Bradford |first=Matt |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/the-wonderful-101-review/ |title=The Wonderful 101 review |website=GamesRadar+ |date=September 11, 2014 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707112505/http://www.gamesradar.com/the-wonderful-101-review/ |archive-date=July 7, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> while others thought these issues were unproblematic thanks to the even distribution of new moves and upgrades.<ref name=\"eurogamer1\"/><ref name=\"nintendolife1\"/>\n\nThe necessity of forming weapons by drawing on the touchscreen garnered a mixed reception. Many reviewers found that the GamePad worked fine for straight lines or circles (to make a sword or a fist), but that it sometimes interpreted more complex shapes as the wrong weapon.<ref name=\"eurogamer1\"/><ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/><ref name=\"gamesradar\"/> Others thought that drawing simple shapes on the GamePad while using the right analogue stick for others was more reliable,<ref name=\"gamespot1\"/> or that the GamePad worked perfectly and it was simply a matter of practice.<ref name=\"nintendolife1\"/><ref name=\"archive1\"/> The camera was criticized for being too zoomed-out to keep track of all of the characters during battle but also too zoomed-in to see the occasional out-of-view enemy.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/><ref name=\"joystiq1\"/><ref name=\"gamesradar\"/> Reviewers agreed that the game lived up to PlatinumGames' trademark high difficulty, with some citing the controls and camera as contributing factors.<ref name=\"gamesradar\"/>\n\nNearly all critics were pleased with the creative uses of the GamePad's second screen.<ref name=\"gamespot1\"/><ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/><ref name=\"gamesradar\"/> However, a few thought that navigating inside of a building using the controller's [[gyroscope]] was clunky.<ref name=\"nintendolife1\"/> Many also thought the multiplayer mode was enjoyable, but often lost track of their own group of characters. Most agreed that it felt \"tacked on\".<ref name=\"gamespot1\"/><ref name=\"archive1\"/> ''The Wonderful 101''{{'s}} cartoony art style and flashy effects in battle were also praised.<ref name=\"eurogamer1\"/><ref name=\"nintendolife1\"/> The set-pieces and giant bosses were likewise well-received, as were the voice acting and soundtrack.<ref name=\"eurogamer1\"/><ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>\n\n===Sales===\nNintendo shipped 30,000 copies for the game's launch in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Ishann|title=The Wonderful 101 Will Launch With Just 30,000 Copies In Japan|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2013/08/19/the-wonderful-101-will-launch-with-just-30000-copies-in-japan|website=Siliconera|accessdate=June 14, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626001401/http://www.siliconera.com/2013/08/19/the-wonderful-101-will-launch-with-just-30000-copies-in-japan|archivedate=June 26, 2014|date=August 19, 2013}}</ref> The game sold 5,258 copies in its first week in Japan<ref name=\"videogamer2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.videogamer.com/wiiu/the_wonderful_101/news/the_wonderful_101_slows_down_wii_u_sales_in_japan.html |title=The Wonderful 101 slows down Wii U sales in Japan |website=VideoGamer.com |date=August 28, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041902/http://www.videogamer.com/wiiu/the_wonderful_101/news/the_wonderful_101_slows_down_wii_u_sales_in_japan.html |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> and reached 22nd place in its first week of the UK sales chart.<ref name=\"videogamer2\"/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Legacy==\nBoth Atsushi Inaba and Hideki Kamiya have expressed interest in a sequel.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Doolan |first1=Liam |title=PlatinumGames Open To Wonderful 101 Sequel, As Long As Fans Show Their Support |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2020/02/platinumgames_open_to_wonderful_101_sequel_as_long_as_fans_show_their_support |website=[[Nintendo Life]] |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |date=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe seven main protagonists appeared as Trophies in ''[[Super Smash Bros. for Wii U]]'', and Wonder-Red and Wonder-Blue appeared as Spirits in ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]''.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://thewonderful101.nintendo.com/}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.platinumgames.com/games/the-wonderful-101|''Remastered'' official website}}\n\n{{Hideki Kamiya}}\n{{PlatinumGames}}\n\n{{